1
00:00:22,731 --> 00:00:25,609
[chime]

2
00:00:27,861 --> 00:00:32,449
[appeasing music]

3
00:00:36,745 --> 00:00:41,083
[fireworks whistling and popping]

4
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:48,465
[crowd cheering]

5
00:00:49,174 --> 00:00:51,760
[Michael Moore]
<i>Was it all just a dream?</i>

6
00:00:52,177 --> 00:00:54,429
God bless you, Florida! Thank you!

7
00:00:55,305 --> 00:00:58,475
[Michael Moore]
<i>Did the last four years not really happen?</i>

8
00:00:59,560 --> 00:01:03,272
<i>Look! There is Ben Affleck.
<i>He's often in my dreams.</i></i>

9
00:01:03,438 --> 00:01:06,441
<i>And the Taxi Driver<i> guy.
<i>He was there too!</i></i></i>

10
00:01:06,608 --> 00:01:10,279
<i>And little Stevie Wonder.
<i>He seemed so happy, like a miracle</i></i>

11
00:01:10,445 --> 00:01:11,947
<i>had taken place.</i>

12
00:01:12,114 --> 00:01:13,198
[crowd cheering]

13
00:01:13,365 --> 00:01:14,783
<i>Was it a dream?</i>

14
00:01:15,367 --> 00:01:17,327
[crowd chanting]

15
00:01:17,494 --> 00:01:19,246
<i>Or was it real?</i>

16
00:01:19,413 --> 00:01:21,123
[country music]

17
00:01:21,290 --> 00:01:23,000
<i>It was election night 2000,</i>

18
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:25,002
<i>and everything seemed
<i>to be going as planned.</i></i>

19
00:01:25,169 --> 00:01:26,211
[TV host]<i> In New York,</i>

20
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:27,588
<i>Al Gore is our projected winner.</i>

21
00:01:27,754 --> 00:01:29,506
<i>The Garden State is green for Gore.</i>

22
00:01:29,673 --> 00:01:32,426
<i>We project Mr. Gore
<i>the winner in Delaware.</i></i>

23
00:01:32,593 --> 00:01:34,511
<i>This state has voted with the winner.</i>

24
00:01:34,678 --> 00:01:36,847
Excuse me one second,
I'm so sorry to interrupt you.

25
00:01:37,014 --> 00:01:39,516
Mike, I wouldn't do this
if it weren't big!

26
00:01:39,683 --> 00:01:41,602
Florida goes for Al Gore.

27
00:01:41,768 --> 00:01:46,023
CNN announces that we call
Florida in the Al Gore column.

28
00:01:47,024 --> 00:01:49,526
[Michael Moore]<i> Then, something
<i>called The Fox News Channel</i></i>

29
00:01:49,693 --> 00:01:51,862
<i>called the election
<i>in favor of the other guy.</i></i>

30
00:01:52,029 --> 00:01:54,031
I interrupt you,
Fox News now projects

31
00:01:54,198 --> 00:01:55,908
George W. Bush the winner in Florida,

32
00:01:56,074 --> 00:01:59,369
and thus it appears the winner
of the Presidency of the United States.

33
00:01:59,536 --> 00:02:01,622
[Michael Moore]<i> All of a sudden,
<i>the other network said:</i></i>

34
00:02:01,788 --> 00:02:04,625
<i>"Hey, if Fox said it, it must be true!"</i>

35
00:02:04,791 --> 00:02:07,628
All of us at the networks
made a mistake

36
00:02:07,794 --> 00:02:10,923
and projected Florida
in the Al Gore column.

37
00:02:11,089 --> 00:02:11,965
It was our mistake.

38
00:02:12,341 --> 00:02:14,635
[Michael Moore]
<i>What most people don't know is</i>

39
00:02:14,801 --> 00:02:18,138
<i>that the man who was in charge
<i>of the decision desk at Fox that night,</i></i>

40
00:02:18,305 --> 00:02:20,682
<i>the man who called it for Bush,
<i>was none other</i></i>

41
00:02:20,849 --> 00:02:23,268
<i>than Bush's first cousin,
<i>John Ellis.</i></i>

42
00:02:23,769 --> 00:02:26,897
<i>How does someone like Bush
<i>get away with something like this?</i></i>

43
00:02:27,064 --> 00:02:29,399
[laughter]

44
00:02:30,317 --> 00:02:32,778
<i>Well, first, it helps
<i>if your brother is the governor</i></i>

45
00:02:32,945 --> 00:02:34,196
<i>of the State in question.</i>

46
00:02:34,363 --> 00:02:36,365
You know something?
We are gonna win Florida.

47
00:02:36,532 --> 00:02:37,991
Mark my words.

48
00:02:38,158 --> 00:02:39,701
You can write it down.

49
00:02:39,868 --> 00:02:43,247
[Michael Moore]<i> Second, make sure
<i>the chairman of your campaign is also</i></i>

50
00:02:43,413 --> 00:02:45,374
<i>the vote count woman,
<i>and that her state</i></i>

51
00:02:45,541 --> 00:02:47,417
<i>has hired a company</i>

52
00:02:47,584 --> 00:02:49,127
<i>that's gonna knock voters
<i>off the rolls</i></i>

53
00:02:49,294 --> 00:02:50,879
<i>who aren't likely to vote for you.</i>

54
00:02:51,630 --> 00:02:54,675
<i>You can usually tell them
<i>by the color of their skin.</i></i>

55
00:02:55,092 --> 00:02:58,136
<i>Then make sure your side fights
<i>like it's life or death.</i></i>

56
00:02:58,303 --> 00:03:02,474
I think all this talk
about legitimacy is way overblown.

57
00:03:02,641 --> 00:03:04,434
[chanting]
President Bush! President Bush!

58
00:03:04,601 --> 00:03:06,436
[Michael Moore]
<i>And hope that the other side</i>

59
00:03:06,603 --> 00:03:09,356
<i>will just sit by
<i>and wait for the phone to ring.</i></i>

60
00:03:10,566 --> 00:03:12,985
<i>And even if numerous
<i>independent investigations prove</i></i>

61
00:03:13,151 --> 00:03:14,903
<i>that Gore got the most votes.</i>

62
00:03:15,070 --> 00:03:17,781
If there was a statewide recount,
under every scenario,

63
00:03:17,948 --> 00:03:19,032
Gore won the election.

64
00:03:19,199 --> 00:03:20,450
[Michael Moore]
<i>It won't matter,</i>

65
00:03:20,617 --> 00:03:23,203
<i>just as long as all your daddy's friends
<i>on the Supreme Court</i></i>

66
00:03:23,370 --> 00:03:24,997
<i>vote the right way.</i>

67
00:03:25,789 --> 00:03:30,836
While I strongly disagree
with the Court's decision, I accept it.

68
00:03:31,003 --> 00:03:34,298
What we need now, is acceptance.

69
00:03:35,215 --> 00:03:37,467
We have a new president-elect.

70
00:03:38,594 --> 00:03:41,638
[Michael Moore]<i> It turns out
<i>none of this was a dream.</i></i>

71
00:03:41,805 --> 00:03:43,640
<i>It's what really happened.</i>

72
00:03:43,807 --> 00:03:45,017
[country music stops]

73
00:03:46,476 --> 00:03:49,479
<i>On the day the joint session
<i>of both the House of Representatives</i></i>

74
00:03:49,646 --> 00:03:53,275
<i>and the Senate was
<i>to certify the election results,</i></i>

75
00:03:53,442 --> 00:03:57,321
<i>Al Gore, in his dual role
<i>as outgoing Vice President</i></i>

76
00:03:57,487 --> 00:03:59,406
<i>and President of the Senate,</i>

77
00:03:59,573 --> 00:04:03,160
<i>presided over the event
<i>that would officially anoint</i></i>

78
00:04:03,327 --> 00:04:05,954
<i>George W. Bush as the new president.</i>

79
00:04:06,121 --> 00:04:10,292
<i>If any congressman wanted to raise
<i>an objection, the rules insisted</i></i>

80
00:04:10,459 --> 00:04:15,255
<i>that he or she had to have the signed
<i>support of just one Senator.</i></i>

81
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:19,927
Mr. President, and I take great pride
in calling you that,

82
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:22,930
I must object because
of the overwhelming evidence

83
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:24,389
of official misconduct.

84
00:04:24,556 --> 00:04:25,557
[protest]

85
00:04:25,724 --> 00:04:27,476
-Deliberate fraud--
-[Al Gore] The Chair

86
00:04:27,643 --> 00:04:30,604
must remind members
that under Section Eighteen

87
00:04:30,771 --> 00:04:33,023
of Title Three, United States Code,

88
00:04:33,190 --> 00:04:34,858
no debate is allowed
in the joint session.

89
00:04:35,025 --> 00:04:37,486
Thank you, Mr. President,
to answer your question,

90
00:04:37,653 --> 00:04:39,571
the objection is in writing,

91
00:04:39,738 --> 00:04:43,325
signed by a number of members
of the House of Representatives,

92
00:04:43,492 --> 00:04:45,619
but not by a member of the Senate.

93
00:04:45,786 --> 00:04:48,413
Uh, Mr. President,
it is in writing and signed

94
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:52,251
by several House colleagues
on behalf, and myself,

95
00:04:52,417 --> 00:04:55,337
of the 27,000 voters of Duval county,

96
00:04:55,504 --> 00:04:59,091
in which 16,000 of them
are African Americans

97
00:04:59,258 --> 00:05:03,011
that was disenfranchised
in this last election.

98
00:05:03,178 --> 00:05:05,722
[Al Gore] Is the objection signed
by a member of the Senate?

99
00:05:05,889 --> 00:05:10,060
Not signed by a member of the Senate,
the Senate is missing.

100
00:05:10,227 --> 00:05:12,729
Mr. President, it is in writing
and signed by myself,

101
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:15,607
on behalf of many of the diverse
constituents in our country,

102
00:05:15,774 --> 00:05:18,193
especially those
in the Ninth Congressional district,

103
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:21,446
and all American voters
who recognize that the Supreme Court,

104
00:05:21,613 --> 00:05:24,366
not the people of the United States,
decided this election.

105
00:05:24,533 --> 00:05:27,035
[Al Gore]
Is the objection signed by a Senator?

106
00:05:27,202 --> 00:05:31,373
Unfortunately, Mr. President,
it is not signed by one single Senator.

107
00:05:31,540 --> 00:05:35,878
Unfortunately, I have no authority
over the United States Senate,

108
00:05:36,044 --> 00:05:37,045
and no Senator has signed.

109
00:05:37,212 --> 00:05:40,299
Mr. President,
it is in writing and signed by myself

110
00:05:40,465 --> 00:05:43,719
and several of my constituents,
constituents from Florida.

111
00:05:43,886 --> 00:05:45,846
A Senator is needed, but missing.

112
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:49,266
[Al Gore]
Is the objection in writing

113
00:05:49,433 --> 00:05:52,644
and signed by a member
of the House and a Senator?

114
00:05:52,811 --> 00:05:55,230
The objection is in writing,
and I don't care

115
00:05:55,397 --> 00:05:58,358
that it is not signed
by a member of the Senate.

116
00:05:58,525 --> 00:06:00,277
-[applause from the bench]
-[hammer]

117
00:06:00,444 --> 00:06:03,572
[Al Gore] The Chair will advise
that the rules do care, and...

118
00:06:03,739 --> 00:06:04,740
[laughter]

119
00:06:04,907 --> 00:06:06,617
[laughter and clapping]

120
00:06:06,783 --> 00:06:08,493
[Al Gore]
The signature of a Senator...

121
00:06:09,536 --> 00:06:12,748
[Michael Moore]<i> Not a single Senator
<i>came to the aid of the African Americans</i></i>

122
00:06:12,915 --> 00:06:13,999
<i>in Congress.</i>

123
00:06:15,083 --> 00:06:17,586
<i>One after another,
<i>they were told to sit down</i></i>

124
00:06:17,753 --> 00:06:19,421
<i>and shut up.</i>

125
00:06:19,588 --> 00:06:22,549
It's a sad day in America,
Mr. President, when we can't find

126
00:06:22,716 --> 00:06:25,761
-a Senator to sign objections.
-[Al Gore] The gentleman!

127
00:06:25,928 --> 00:06:27,221
The gentleman will suspend.

128
00:06:27,387 --> 00:06:30,307
Won't sign objections,
Mr. President, I object!

129
00:06:30,682 --> 00:06:32,434
[Al Gore]
The gentleman will suspend.

130
00:06:32,601 --> 00:06:34,978
[sad music]

131
00:06:35,145 --> 00:06:37,439
[Peter Jennings]
<i>Inauguration coverage 2001</i>

132
00:06:37,606 --> 00:06:41,109
<i>on a nasty, but it could be
<i>a worse kind of day in Washington.</i></i>

133
00:06:41,276 --> 00:06:42,903
-<i>What do we want?
-Justice!</i>

134
00:06:43,070 --> 00:06:44,488
-<i>When do we want it?
-Now!</i>

135
00:06:44,655 --> 00:06:45,531
[crowd cheering]

136
00:06:45,697 --> 00:06:48,450
[Michael Moore] <i>On the day
<i>that George W. Bush was inaugurated,</i></i>

137
00:06:48,617 --> 00:06:52,871
<i>tens of thousands of Americans
<i>poured into the streets of D.C.</i></i>

138
00:06:53,038 --> 00:06:55,958
<i>in one last attempt to reclaim
<i>what had been taken from them.</i></i>

139
00:06:56,124 --> 00:06:58,085
[crowd protesting]

140
00:06:59,378 --> 00:07:01,755
<i>They pelted Bush's limo with eggs.</i>

141
00:07:01,922 --> 00:07:02,798
[egg crashing]

142
00:07:02,965 --> 00:07:04,299
[policeman]
Get back! Get back!

143
00:07:04,466 --> 00:07:07,386
[Michael Moore]<i> And brought
<i>the inauguration parade to a halt.</i></i>

144
00:07:07,553 --> 00:07:08,762
[screams]

145
00:07:08,929 --> 00:07:11,974
<i>The plan to have Bush get out
<i>of the limo for the traditional walk</i></i>

146
00:07:12,140 --> 00:07:14,351
<i>to the White House was scrapped.</i>

147
00:07:14,518 --> 00:07:18,272
<i>Bush's limo hit the gas
<i>to prevent an even larger riot.</i></i>

148
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:19,523
[crowd protesting]

149
00:07:19,690 --> 00:07:24,236
<i>No president had ever witnessed
<i>such a thing on his Inauguration Day.</i></i>

150
00:07:24,403 --> 00:07:27,281
[crowd booing]

151
00:07:29,241 --> 00:07:30,826
[sad guitar tune]

152
00:07:30,993 --> 00:07:32,870
<i>And for the next eight months,</i>

153
00:07:33,036 --> 00:07:36,123
<i>it didn't get any better
<i>for George W. Bush.</i></i>

154
00:07:37,332 --> 00:07:40,127
<i>He couldn't get his judges appointed.</i>

155
00:07:40,294 --> 00:07:43,463
<i>He had trouble getting
<i>his legislation passed,</i></i>

156
00:07:43,630 --> 00:07:46,508
<i>and he lost Republican control
<i>of the Senate.</i></i>

157
00:07:47,634 --> 00:07:50,762
<i>His approval ratings
<i>in the polls began to sink.</i></i>

158
00:07:51,138 --> 00:07:54,391
<i>He was already beginning
<i>to look like a lame duck president.</i></i>

159
00:07:55,017 --> 00:07:56,727
<i>With everything going wrong,</i>

160
00:07:56,894 --> 00:07:59,021
<i>he did what any of us would do.</i>

161
00:07:59,646 --> 00:08:01,607
<i>He went on vacation.</i>

162
00:08:02,191 --> 00:08:05,652
[The Go-Go's "Vacation" playing]

163
00:08:05,819 --> 00:08:08,655
♪<i> Vacation, had to get away ♪</i>

164
00:08:08,822 --> 00:08:12,409
♪<i> Vacation, meant to spend alone ♪</i>

165
00:08:14,244 --> 00:08:15,120
[hitting ball]

166
00:08:15,287 --> 00:08:16,330
Oh, no!

167
00:08:16,496 --> 00:08:19,791
[Michael Moore]<i> In his first eight
<i>months in office before September 11th,</i></i>

168
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:23,962
<i>George W. Bush was on vacation,
<i>according to the Washington Post,</i></i>

169
00:08:24,129 --> 00:08:25,923
<i>42% of the time.</i>

170
00:08:26,089 --> 00:08:28,967
If I hit every shot good,
people would say I wasn't working.

171
00:08:29,134 --> 00:08:33,222
[Michael Moore]<i> It was not surprising
<i>that Mr. Bush needed some time off.</i></i>

172
00:08:33,388 --> 00:08:35,849
<i>Being president is a lot of work.</i>

173
00:08:36,016 --> 00:08:38,268
[female reporter]
What about these folks that say

174
00:08:38,435 --> 00:08:40,229
you're taking too long of a vacation?

175
00:08:41,104 --> 00:08:43,357
They don't understand
the definition of work, then.

176
00:08:43,524 --> 00:08:45,025
[crowd chatter]

177
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:46,318
I'm getting a lot done.

178
00:08:46,485 --> 00:08:49,279
Secondly, you don't have to be
in Washington to work.

179
00:08:49,863 --> 00:08:52,783
It's, uh... It's amazing, uh,

180
00:08:52,950 --> 00:08:55,244
what can happen
with telephones and faxes.

181
00:08:55,410 --> 00:08:57,371
[woman]
Thank you so much, you were great.

182
00:08:57,538 --> 00:08:59,414
[inaudible chatter]

183
00:08:59,581 --> 00:09:01,834
[male reporter] What are you doing
the rest of the day?

184
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,003
Karen Hughes is coming over,
we're working on some things,

185
00:09:05,170 --> 00:09:06,880
and uh...

186
00:09:07,464 --> 00:09:10,551
She'll be over here, we'll be working
on a few things, a few matters.

187
00:09:10,717 --> 00:09:12,469
I'm working on some initiatives.

188
00:09:13,846 --> 00:09:15,180
We're, uh... You'll see!

189
00:09:15,347 --> 00:09:18,267
I mean, I've got-- There'll be
some decisions that I will have made

190
00:09:18,433 --> 00:09:21,061
while I'm here, and we'll be
announcing them as time goes on.

191
00:09:21,228 --> 00:09:23,355
[Michael Moore]
<i>The first time I met him,</i>

192
00:09:23,522 --> 00:09:25,190
<i>he had some good advice for me.</i>

193
00:09:25,357 --> 00:09:28,360
-Governor Bush, it's Michael Moore!
-Behave yourself, will you?

194
00:09:29,361 --> 00:09:30,696
Go find real work!

195
00:09:30,863 --> 00:09:31,780
[laughter]

196
00:09:31,947 --> 00:09:34,366
[Michael Moore]<i> And work was
<i>something he knew a lot about!</i></i>

197
00:09:34,533 --> 00:09:36,118
-[reporter calling him]
-Anybody want some grits?

198
00:09:36,535 --> 00:09:37,452
-Yeah!
-[laughing]

199
00:09:37,619 --> 00:09:39,830
[Michael Moore]
<i>Relaxing at Camp David.</i>

200
00:09:39,997 --> 00:09:41,999
<i>Yachting off Kennebunkport.</i>

201
00:09:42,165 --> 00:09:44,042
-How ya doing?
-[patting]

202
00:09:44,877 --> 00:09:47,796
[Michael Moore]<i> Or being a cowboy
<i>on a ranch in Texas.</i></i>

203
00:09:47,963 --> 00:09:51,383
I love the nature, I love to get
in the pickup truck with my dogs.

204
00:09:51,967 --> 00:09:52,885
Oh, hi!

205
00:09:53,051 --> 00:09:56,180
[Michael Moore]<i> George Bush spent
<i>the rest of August at the ranch,</i></i>

206
00:09:56,346 --> 00:09:58,265
<i>where life was less complicated.</i>

207
00:09:58,432 --> 00:10:01,185
Armadillos love to dig
the soil looking for bugs.

208
00:10:02,186 --> 00:10:03,312
And...

209
00:10:04,521 --> 00:10:08,025
So I went out there the other day,
and there was Barney!

210
00:10:09,067 --> 00:10:12,529
Buried in this hole,
chasing an armadillo.

211
00:10:12,696 --> 00:10:13,697
[laughing]

212
00:10:13,864 --> 00:10:16,366
[Michael Moore]
<i>It was a summer to remember.</i>

213
00:10:16,533 --> 00:10:18,911
<i>And when it was over,
<i>he left Texas</i></i>

214
00:10:19,411 --> 00:10:21,246
<i>for his second favorite place.</i>

215
00:10:21,705 --> 00:10:24,541
<i>On September tenth,
<i>he joined his brother in Florida,</i></i>

216
00:10:24,708 --> 00:10:28,086
<i>where he looked at files
<i>and met important Floridians.</i></i>

217
00:10:29,588 --> 00:10:34,927
<i>He went to sleep that night in a bed
<i>made with fine French linens.</i></i>

218
00:10:35,093 --> 00:10:39,056
[Jeff Gibbs's<i> Fahrenheit 9/11
intro theme song]</i>

219
00:10:39,223 --> 00:10:45,270
[slow guitar tune]

220
00:10:52,402 --> 00:10:54,071
[Donald Rumsfeld]
Do you suppose he's pretty

221
00:10:54,238 --> 00:10:56,990
confident on those numbers
on Iraqi security forces?

222
00:11:15,175 --> 00:11:16,593
