and said that the CIA was very concerned

1091
00:56:48,200 --> 00:56:50,077
that there would be an attack.

1092
00:56:50,244 --> 00:56:53,539
You said that you told
the Attorney General

1093
00:56:53,705 --> 00:56:56,583
this fact repeatedly in these meetings.
Is that correct?

1094
00:56:56,750 --> 00:56:58,085
[Thomas Pickard] I told him

1095
00:56:58,252 --> 00:56:59,795
at least on two occasions.

1096
00:56:59,962 --> 00:57:01,672
[Ben Veniste] And you told the staff,

1097
00:57:01,839 --> 00:57:04,925
according to this statement,
that Mr. Ashcroft told you

1098
00:57:05,092 --> 00:57:07,845
that he did not want to hear
about this anymore.

1099
00:57:08,011 --> 00:57:09,221
Is that correct?

1100
00:57:09,763 --> 00:57:10,681
That is correct.

1101
00:57:10,848 --> 00:57:12,224
[Michael Moore]
<i>His own FBI knew that summer</i>

1102
00:57:12,391 --> 00:57:15,477
<i>that there were
<i>Al-Qaeda members in the U.S.,</i></i>

1103
00:57:15,644 --> 00:57:18,313
<i>and that Bin Laden was sending
<i>his agents to flight schools</i></i>

1104
00:57:18,480 --> 00:57:20,274
<i>around the country.</i>

1105
00:57:20,440 --> 00:57:25,445
<i>But Ashcroft's Justice Department
<i>turned a blind eye and a deaf ear.</i></i>

1106
00:57:25,904 --> 00:57:29,908
<i>But after 9/11,
<i>John Ashcroft had some brilliant ideas</i></i>

1107
00:57:30,075 --> 00:57:31,952
<i>for how to protect America.</i>

1108
00:57:32,119 --> 00:57:34,496
[Elizabeth Hashagen]<i> The U.S.A.
<i>PATRIOT Act adopted by Congress</i></i>

1109
00:57:34,663 --> 00:57:37,207
<i>and signed by Bush
<i>six weeks after the attacks</i></i>

1110
00:57:37,374 --> 00:57:39,293
<i>changed the way
<i>the government does business.</i></i>

1111
00:57:39,459 --> 00:57:42,504
<i>The U.S.A. PATRIOT Act
<i>allows for searches of medical</i></i>

1112
00:57:42,671 --> 00:57:45,632
<i>and financial records,
<i>computer and telephone conversations,</i></i>

1113
00:57:45,799 --> 00:57:48,093
<i>and even for the books
<i>you take out of the library.</i></i>

1114
00:57:48,260 --> 00:57:50,220
<i>But most of the people we spoke to</i>

1115
00:57:50,387 --> 00:57:53,724
<i>say they're willing to give up
<i>some liberties to fight terrorism.</i></i>

1116
00:57:53,891 --> 00:57:54,975
Maybe that's a good thing.

1117
00:57:55,142 --> 00:57:58,228
It's definitely sad,
but it has to be done.

1118
00:57:58,687 --> 00:58:01,148
[Michael Moore]
<i>Yes, something needed to be done.</i>

1119
00:58:01,315 --> 00:58:02,316
[joyous music]

1120
00:58:02,482 --> 00:58:05,485
<i>These are the good people
<i>who make up Peace Fresno.</i></i>

1121
00:58:06,028 --> 00:58:08,071
<i>A community group in Fresno, California.</i>

1122
00:58:09,323 --> 00:58:10,991
<i>Unlike the rest of us,</i>

1123
00:58:11,158 --> 00:58:15,245
<i>they've received an early lesson
<i>in what the PATRIOT Act is all about.</i></i>

1124
00:58:15,787 --> 00:58:19,499
<i>Each week they meet
<i>to discuss matters of peace!</i></i>

1125
00:58:20,334 --> 00:58:22,878
<i>They sit around, they share stories.</i>

1126
00:58:23,670 --> 00:58:24,963
<i>They eat cookies.</i>

1127
00:58:25,797 --> 00:58:27,633
<i>Some have more than one.</i>

1128
00:58:27,799 --> 00:58:29,092
[laughter]

1129
00:58:29,259 --> 00:58:31,220
<i>This is Aaron Stokes,</i>

1130
00:58:31,386 --> 00:58:32,763
<i>a member of Peace Fresno.</i>

1131
00:58:33,764 --> 00:58:35,307
<i>The other members liked him.</i>

1132
00:58:35,474 --> 00:58:38,018
[Eugenie Baranoff] <i>He had come
<i>to the meetings, he went with us,</i></i>

1133
00:58:38,185 --> 00:58:39,478
we'd go out on Friday nights

1134
00:58:39,645 --> 00:58:42,314
and stand
on a very busy corner in Fresno,

1135
00:58:42,481 --> 00:58:45,692
and he had gone with us,
he had handed out flyers,

1136
00:58:45,859 --> 00:58:49,863
he went with us in June
to a W.T.O. protest.

1137
00:58:50,030 --> 00:58:52,783
[Michael Moore]<i> Then one day,
<i>Aaron didn't show up to the meeting.</i></i>

1138
00:58:53,242 --> 00:58:56,537
My friend Dan and I were reading
the Sunday newspaper,

1139
00:58:56,703 --> 00:59:00,123
and when I picked up the paper,
in the local section,

1140
00:59:00,290 --> 00:59:01,959
<i>Aaron's picture caught my eye.</i>

1141
00:59:02,125 --> 00:59:05,420
<i>The article said that a Sheriff's
<i>deputy had been killed</i></i>

1142
00:59:05,587 --> 00:59:08,841
<i>and I saw it had a name
<i>that wasn't the right name.</i></i>

1143
00:59:09,007 --> 00:59:14,346
<i>It said that he was a member
<i>of the sheriff's anti-terrorism Unit.</i></i>

1144
00:59:14,972 --> 00:59:16,306
[Michael Moore] <i>That's right!</i>

1145
00:59:16,473 --> 00:59:18,851
<i>The photo of the man in the newspaper</i>

1146
00:59:19,017 --> 00:59:22,563
<i>was not the Aaron Stokes
<i>they had come to know.</i></i>

1147
00:59:22,729 --> 00:59:25,816
<i>He was actually Deputy Aaron Kilner</i>

1148
00:59:25,983 --> 00:59:28,110
<i>and he had infiltrated their group.</i>

1149
00:59:29,111 --> 00:59:32,030
[Catherine Campbell] <i>Sheriff Pierce
<i>made it very clear that yes, in fact,</i></i>

1150
00:59:32,197 --> 00:59:35,033
<i>Aaron Kilner was assigned
<i>to infiltrate Peace Fresno,</i></i>

1151
00:59:35,200 --> 00:59:38,495
that he was able
to infiltrate organizations

1152
00:59:38,662 --> 00:59:40,372
that are open to the public.

1153
00:59:40,956 --> 00:59:42,875
[Michael Moore]
<i>You could understand why the police</i>

1154
00:59:43,041 --> 00:59:45,419
<i>needed to spy on a group
<i>like Peace Fresno.</i></i>

1155
00:59:45,878 --> 00:59:46,795
<i>Just look at them!</i>

1156
00:59:48,797 --> 00:59:50,966
<i>A gathering of terrorists,
<i>if I ever saw one!</i></i>

1157
00:59:51,133 --> 00:59:52,259
[music fades away]

1158
00:59:53,051 --> 00:59:57,514
<i>This is Barry Reingold, a retired
<i>phone worker from Oakland, California.</i></i>

1159
00:59:57,681 --> 00:59:58,599
[heroic tune]

1160
00:59:59,057 --> 01:00:01,852
<i>Barry likes to work out in the gym.</i>

1161
01:00:02,019 --> 01:00:05,397
<i>Somewhere between his cardio
<i>and his strength training,</i></i>

1162
01:00:05,564 --> 01:00:07,274
<i>Barry got political.</i>

1163
01:00:08,025 --> 01:00:11,778
We were up in the gym
and it was after we were working out

1164
01:00:11,945 --> 01:00:16,450
and a number of us were talking
about 9/11 and Afghanistan and Bin Laden,

1165
01:00:16,617 --> 01:00:18,493
and someone said:

1166
01:00:18,660 --> 01:00:21,872
"Bin Laden's a real asshole
for murdering those people."

1167
01:00:22,039 --> 01:00:24,041
and I said: "Yeah that's true!

1168
01:00:24,208 --> 01:00:27,586
But he will never be
as big an asshole as Bush,

1169
01:00:27,753 --> 01:00:30,422
who bombs all over
the world for oil profits."

1170
01:00:30,589 --> 01:00:33,842
[Michael Moore]<i> Barry didn't have
<i>to worry about the police spying on him.</i></i>

1171
01:00:34,801 --> 01:00:38,263
<i>His fellow weight lifters were
<i>more than willing to turn him in.</i></i>

1172
01:00:38,430 --> 01:00:41,642
I was taking a nap,
and I guess it was 1:30 p.m.,

1173
01:00:41,808 --> 01:00:43,227
two o'clock in the afternoon,

1174
01:00:43,560 --> 01:00:46,605
<i>and they came to my place and I said:</i>

1175
01:00:46,772 --> 01:00:49,274
"Well, who's there?"
and they said: "The FBI."

1176
01:00:49,441 --> 01:00:50,567
I said: "The FBI?"

1177
01:00:50,734 --> 01:00:52,694
I mean, why are they here?

1178
01:00:52,861 --> 01:00:54,821
[Michael Moore]
<i>Yes, the FBI had come to see Barry,</i>

1179
01:00:55,781 --> 01:00:58,200
<i>and they weren't
<i>there to Jazzercize.</i></i>

1180
01:00:58,367 --> 01:00:59,952
[Barry] <i>The FBI said:</i>

1181
01:01:00,118 --> 01:01:02,538
"Have you been talking
to people about 9/11

1182
01:01:02,704 --> 01:01:07,209
and about Bin Laden
and oil profits and Afghanistan?"

1183
01:01:07,376 --> 01:01:10,671
I said: "A lot of people
are talking about these things."

1184
01:01:10,838 --> 01:01:14,883
And I feel my rights have been,
you know, trampled on.

1185
01:01:15,050 --> 01:01:19,096
I mean, if you have something
to say to me in the gym, well, then, fine!

1186
01:01:19,263 --> 01:01:24,309
Don't tell the FBI and they come
to my apartment while I'm taking a nap.

1187
01:01:24,726 --> 01:01:27,813
There's nothing to be ashamed of here.
There is full transparency.

1188
01:01:27,980 --> 01:01:31,275
There is nothing about the PATRIOT Act
that I am ashamed of

1189
01:01:31,441 --> 01:01:33,402
in any way, shape or form.

1190
01:01:33,569 --> 01:01:35,737
I have a 1-800 number, call me!

1191
01:01:35,904 --> 01:01:39,408
I'm the guy you call,
if there's a violation or abuse.

1192
01:01:39,575 --> 01:01:42,953
If you've got a poster child on this,
I wanna see it, that's what I do.

1193
01:01:43,120 --> 01:01:45,831
I'm hired by the people
of the United States to provide oversight,

1194
01:01:45,998 --> 01:01:47,124
I provide oversight.

1195
01:01:47,291 --> 01:01:50,335
Trent Lott said
the day the bill was introduced:

1196
01:01:50,502 --> 01:01:54,590
"Maybe now we can do things we've wanted
to do for the last ten years."

1197
01:01:55,215 --> 01:01:57,926
You know, a dictatorship
would be a heck of a lot easier,

1198
01:01:58,093 --> 01:01:59,636
-it's no question about it.
-[laughter]

1199
01:01:59,803 --> 01:02:03,974
I mean, they had all this
on the shelf somewhere,

1200
01:02:04,141 --> 01:02:06,852
ideas of things they would like to do.

1201
01:02:07,019 --> 01:02:11,023
And they got 9/11 and they said:
"It's our chance! Go for it!"

1202
01:02:11,190 --> 01:02:15,277
There was an immediate assumption
on the part of the Administration

1203
01:02:15,444 --> 01:02:20,574
that there had to be a surrender
of certain of our rights.

1204
01:02:20,741 --> 01:02:23,243
There's several definitions
in the Bill that are quite troubling.

1205
01:02:23,410 --> 01:02:25,871
First of all,
the definition of "terrorist"!

1206
01:02:26,038 --> 01:02:31,960
It's so expansive
that it could include people--

1207
01:02:32,127 --> 01:02:33,670
-[Michael Moore] Like me?
-[laughing]

1208
01:02:33,837 --> 01:02:36,340
No one read it, that's the whole point!

1209
01:02:36,507 --> 01:02:39,426
They wait till the middle of the night,
they drop it in the middle of the night,

1210
01:02:39,593 --> 01:02:41,470
it's printed in the middle of the night,

1211
01:02:41,637 --> 01:02:43,972
and the next morning
when we come in, it passes.

1212
01:02:44,139 --> 01:02:46,183
[Michael Moore]
Erm, how could Congress

1213
01:02:46,350 --> 01:02:49,728
pass this PATRIOT Act
without even reading it?

1214
01:02:49,895 --> 01:02:51,188
Sit down, my son!

1215
01:02:52,314 --> 01:02:55,359
Uh, we don't read most of the bills.

1216
01:02:55,526 --> 01:02:57,194
[ethereal music]

1217
01:02:57,361 --> 01:03:00,113
Do you really know what that would entail

1218
01:03:00,280 --> 01:03:04,326
if we were to read every bill
that we pass?

1219
01:03:05,827 --> 01:03:07,162
Uh...

1220
01:03:07,746 --> 01:03:11,416
Well the good thing, it would slow down
the legislative process.

1221
01:03:11,583 --> 01:03:15,379
[Michael Moore]<i> I couldn't believe that
<i>virtually no member of Congress had read</i></i>

1222
01:03:15,546 --> 01:03:17,756
<i>the PATRIOT Act before voting on it.</i>

1223
01:03:17,923 --> 01:03:22,261
<i>So I decided the only
<i>patriotic thing to do was for me</i></i>

1224
01:03:22,427 --> 01:03:23,971
<i>to read it to them.</i>

1225
01:03:24,137 --> 01:03:25,305
[ice cream van music]

1226
01:03:25,472 --> 01:03:28,058
[on loudspeaker]<i> Members of Congress,
<i>this is Michael Moore!</i></i>

1227
01:03:28,225 --> 01:03:30,769
<i>I would like to read you
<i>the U.S.A. PATRIOT Act!</i></i>

1228
01:03:30,936 --> 01:03:35,816
<i>Section one, section 210
<i>of this code reads as follows!</i></i>

1229
01:03:35,983 --> 01:03:37,776
<i>Section 2703 C.</i>

1230
01:03:37,943 --> 01:03:41,572
My job is to secure the homeland
and that's exactly what we're going to do.

1231
01:03:41,738 --> 01:03:43,365
But I'm here to take somebody's order.

1232
01:03:43,532 --> 01:03:45,200
-[accordion playing]
-[laughter]

1233
01:03:45,367 --> 01:03:46,952
That would be you, Stretch,
what would you like?

1234
01:03:47,119 --> 01:03:49,496
-Right behind you!
-I'm gonna order some ribs!

1235
01:03:49,663 --> 01:03:53,208
[Michael Moore]<i> We all know you can't
<i>secure the homeland on an empty stomach.</i></i>

1236
01:03:53,375 --> 01:03:57,754
<i>And in order to remain secure,
<i>everyone needs to sacrifice.</i></i>

1237
01:03:58,755 --> 01:04:01,466
<i>Especially little Patrick Hamilton.</i>

1238
01:04:02,593 --> 01:04:07,181
<i>I'm sure each of us has our own personal
<i>airport security horror story.</i></i>

1239
01:04:08,348 --> 01:04:09,683
<i>But here's my favorite:</i>

1240
01:04:10,767 --> 01:04:15,147
<i>the terrorist threat that was posed
<i>by his mommy's breast milk.</i></i>

1241
01:04:15,314 --> 01:04:18,901
I thought if I just put a little bit
on my lips, then that would be sufficient

1242
01:04:19,067 --> 01:04:20,444
because obviously I'm tasting it.

1243
01:04:20,611 --> 01:04:23,113
And she looked at me
and I felt like she was telling me:

1244
01:04:23,280 --> 01:04:26,366
"You need to chug that."
She goes: "No, you need to drink more."

1245
01:04:26,533 --> 01:04:30,871
And of a four ounce bottle, I wound up
drinking two more ounces of breast milk

1246
01:04:31,038 --> 01:04:33,874
that, then, because it's touched my lips,
has to be tossed.

1247
01:04:34,499 --> 01:04:37,169
[Michael Moore]<i> While Homeland Security
<i>was making sure breast milk</i></i>

1248
01:04:37,336 --> 01:04:38,837
<i>was kept off our planes,</i>

1249
01:04:39,338 --> 01:04:41,173
<i>they were also doing everything possible</i>

1250
01:04:41,340 --> 01:04:44,510
<i>to ensure no one
<i>could light a fire bomb on board.</i></i>

1251
01:04:44,676 --> 01:04:46,303
[passenger]
I can bring that on the plane?

1252
01:04:46,470 --> 01:04:48,889
[officer]
Actually, you can, yes, you're fine.

1253
01:04:49,056 --> 01:04:50,807
Oops! One too many books of matches.

1254
01:04:50,974 --> 01:04:53,685
You can have four books of matches
and two lighters.

1255
01:04:53,852 --> 01:04:57,314
When we already have the experience
of Richard Reid, the shoe bomber,

1256
01:04:57,481 --> 01:04:58,482
who would have

1257
01:04:58,649 --> 01:05:00,400
<i>blown up an airplane with his shoe bomb,</i>

1258
01:05:00,567 --> 01:05:02,486
<i>had he had a butane lighter,
<i>according to the FBI,</i></i>

1259
01:05:02,653 --> 01:05:05,197
why would the Transportation
Security Agency say it's okay

1260
01:05:05,364 --> 01:05:07,699
to take four books of matches
and two lighters in your pockets

1261
01:05:07,866 --> 01:05:08,867
as you board an airplane?

1262
01:05:09,034 --> 01:05:10,702
<i>I'm guessing that somebody</i>

1263
01:05:10,869 --> 01:05:13,497
<i>put pressure on them to say, you know:</i>

1264
01:05:13,664 --> 01:05:15,916
<i>"When an airplane lands,
<i>people want to light up pretty quickly,</i></i>

1265
01:05:16,083 --> 01:05:17,376
so don't take their lighters away."

1266
01:05:17,543 --> 01:05:19,545
[Michael Moore]
<i>OK, let me see if I got this straight!</i>

1267
01:05:19,711 --> 01:05:21,630
<i>Old guys in the gym? Bad.</i>

1268
01:05:21,797 --> 01:05:23,549
<i>Peace groups in Fresno? Bad.</i>

1269
01:05:23,715 --> 01:05:25,676
<i>Breast milk? Really bad.</i>

1270
01:05:25,843 --> 01:05:28,345
<i>But matches and lighters on a plane?
<i>Oh, hey, no problem!</i></i>

1271
01:05:28,512 --> 01:05:33,559
<i>Was this really about our safety?
<i>Or was something else going on?</i></i>

1272
01:05:33,725 --> 01:05:35,435
[waves]

1273
01:05:35,602 --> 01:05:40,566
<i>This is where the Pacific Ocean
<i>meets the shores of Oregon,</i></i>

1274
01:05:40,732 --> 01:05:44,444
<i>over 100 miles of beautiful
<i>open coastline on our border.</i></i>

1275
01:05:45,320 --> 01:05:48,156
<i>And, thanks to the budget cutbacks,</i>

1276
01:05:48,991 --> 01:05:51,743
<i>the total number of State police
<i>protecting it...</i></i>

1277
01:05:52,953 --> 01:05:54,079
<i>One!</i>

1278
01:05:55,581 --> 01:05:56,790
<i>Part-time.</i>

1279
01:05:57,791 --> 01:05:59,126
<i>Meet trooper Brooks.</i>

1280
01:06:00,002 --> 01:06:03,672
[trooper Brooks] I maybe get a chance
to hit this stretch of highway

1281
01:06:03,839 --> 01:06:07,259
once, maybe twice
a week during my shifts.

1282
01:06:07,426 --> 01:06:11,221
Um, you know,
it's just to even drive up here and look.

1283
01:06:12,306 --> 01:06:13,765
You know, I mean, as far as I know,

1284
01:06:13,932 --> 01:06:16,059
somebody could...
There's lot of things they could do.

1285
01:06:16,226 --> 01:06:19,438
I don't even want to suspect,
because it just makes me ill inside.

1286
01:06:19,605 --> 01:06:21,732
[Michael Moore]
<i>Back at the State trooper patrol office,</i>

1287
01:06:21,899 --> 01:06:26,653
<i>thanks to the budget cuts, trooper Kenyon
<i>had to come in on his day off to catch up</i></i>

1288
01:06:26,820 --> 01:06:28,155
<i>on some paperwork.</i>

1289
01:06:28,322 --> 01:06:31,074
For the most part, especially during
the summertime, when people show up,

1290
01:06:31,241 --> 01:06:33,535
this is exactly what they get,
they close the door,

1291
01:06:33,702 --> 01:06:36,371
they can read the sign
about the office closure,

1292
01:06:36,538 --> 01:06:39,958
and, it just basically explains that,
you know, due to our cutbacks,

1293
01:06:40,125 --> 01:06:42,920
that our office is not open
for administrative business.

1294
01:06:43,086 --> 01:06:46,089
There's a little sign down at the bottom
that explains when the office is closed.

1295
01:06:46,256 --> 01:06:51,762
And that they can use the phone booth
to get in touch with our dispatch.

1296
01:06:52,471 --> 01:06:55,933
Ironically enough, that phone is a piece
of junk, it doesn't work very well,

1297
01:06:56,099 --> 01:06:58,435
so, half the time,
when they pick up the phone

1298
01:06:58,602 --> 01:07:02,272
and dispatch gets a bunch of static
and they don't hear anything.

1299
01:07:02,898 --> 01:07:05,943
For Tuesday,
there'll be no troop on patrol.

1300
01:07:06,109 --> 01:07:07,903
Wednesday,
there'll be no troop on patrol.

1301
01:07:08,070 --> 01:07:10,239
Thursday,
there'll be no troop on patrol

1302
01:07:10,405 --> 01:07:14,034
You get calls all the time,
people will call in a suspicious vehicle,

1303
01:07:14,201 --> 01:07:16,662
or somebody looking suspicious,
you know...

1304
01:07:16,828 --> 01:07:19,831
And I don't hardly ever respond
to that anymore.

1305
01:07:19,998 --> 01:07:21,375
I just don't have the time to do it.

1306
01:07:21,542 --> 01:07:23,961
One night I asked: "How many people
do we have in this state of Oregon

1307
01:07:24,127 --> 01:07:25,838
on duty tonight?"

1308
01:07:26,004 --> 01:07:30,717
And we had eight troopers on
for the entire state of Oregon working.

1309
01:07:32,970 --> 01:07:35,889
I think, you know,
Oregon is a prime example

1310
01:07:36,056 --> 01:07:39,226
that homeland security
is not as secure as what,

1311
01:07:39,393 --> 01:07:41,603
I think, people would like to believe.

1312
01:07:41,770 --> 01:07:44,606
Nobody's sent me any manual that says
here's how you catch a terrorist,

1313
01:07:44,773 --> 01:07:47,568
you know,
and if I had that manual, I'd read it.

1314
01:07:47,734 --> 01:07:49,069
But I don't, so...

1315
01:07:50,279 --> 01:07:51,280
Yeah...

1316
01:07:52,698 --> 01:07:55,450
[Michael Moore]<i> Of course, the Bush
<i>administration didn't hand out a manual</i></i>

1317
01:07:55,617 --> 01:07:57,327
<i>on how to deal with the terrorist threat,</i>

1318
01:07:57,494 --> 01:08:01,540
<i>because the terrorist threat wasn't
<i>what this was all about.</i></i>

1319
01:08:02,416 --> 01:08:04,793
<i>They just wanted us to be fearful enough</i>

1320
01:08:04,960 --> 01:08:08,630
<i>so that we'd get behind
<i>what their real plan was.</i></i>

1321
01:08:09,631 --> 01:08:13,427
[metallic rustling]

1322
01:08:13,594 --> 01:08:14,761
[female voice]
<i>Four minutes!</i>

1323
01:08:14,928 --> 01:08:15,888
Start from the top!

1324
01:08:16,054 --> 01:08:18,056
[cameraman]
Okay. Alright?

1325
01:08:18,223 --> 01:08:20,142
-[fiddling]
-How much time?

1326
01:08:20,309 --> 01:08:22,352
-[female voice]<i> Three minutes!
-[director]<i> Stand by!</i></i>

1327
01:08:22,519 --> 01:08:25,355
[inaudible directions]

1328
01:08:25,522 --> 01:08:26,732
[female voice]
<i>30 seconds!</i>

1329
01:08:26,899 --> 01:08:28,901
[airplane throbbing]

1330
01:08:29,067 --> 01:08:30,402
[woman off-screen] Fifteen seconds!

1331
01:08:33,614 --> 01:08:38,493
Ten, nine, eight, seven, six, five,

1332
01:08:38,660 --> 01:08:42,372
four, three, two, one.

1333
01:08:43,123 --> 01:08:44,249
My fellow citizens!

1334
01:08:44,416 --> 01:08:48,420
[general street noise and chatter]

1335
01:08:48,587 --> 01:08:51,507
[crowd noise]

1336
01:08:51,673 --> 01:08:55,219
[kids screaming]

1337
01:08:55,385 --> 01:08:59,306
[traffic noise]

1338
01:08:59,473 --> 01:09:00,516
[sound of clippers]

1339
01:09:00,682 --> 01:09:04,937
[chat in Arabic]

1340
01:09:05,103 --> 01:09:07,981
[restaurant activity]

1341
01:09:08,148 --> 01:09:09,107
[inaudible]

1342
01:09:09,274 --> 01:09:12,277
[bike squeaking]

1343
01:09:12,444 --> 01:09:14,071
[kids chatting]

1344
01:09:15,405 --> 01:09:17,282
-[birds chirping]
-[kids laughing]

1345
01:09:17,449 --> 01:09:18,659
[George W. Bush]
<i>At this hour,</i>

1346
01:09:18,825 --> 01:09:23,288
<i>American and coalition forces are
<i>in the early stages of military operations</i></i>

1347
01:09:23,455 --> 01:09:28,794
<i>to disarm Iraq, to free its people,
<i>and to defend the world from grave danger.</i></i>

1348
01:09:28,961 --> 01:09:33,048
<i>On my orders, coalition forces have begun
<i>striking selected targets</i></i>

1349
01:09:33,215 --> 01:09:36,093
<i>of military importance
<i>to undermine Saddam Hussein's</i></i>

1350
01:09:36,260 --> 01:09:38,095
<i>ability to wage a war.</i>

1351
01:09:38,262 --> 01:09:39,137
[sliding sound]

1352
01:09:39,304 --> 01:09:41,682
[repetitive explosions]

1353
01:09:50,190 --> 01:09:55,112
[sirens ringing]

1354
01:10:01,076 --> 01:10:04,037
[Michael Moore]<i> On March 19th, 2003,</i>

1355
01:10:04,204 --> 01:10:07,457
<i>George W. Bush
<i>and the United States military</i></i>

1356
01:10:07,624 --> 01:10:09,960
<i>invaded the sovereign nation of Iraq.</i>

1357
01:10:10,127 --> 01:10:11,253
[explosion]

1358
01:10:11,420 --> 01:10:14,464
<i>A nation that had never attacked
<i>the United States.</i></i>

1359
01:10:14,631 --> 01:10:16,341
[explosion]

1360
01:10:16,508 --> 01:10:20,429
<i>A nation that had never threatened
<i>to attack the Unites States.</i></i>

1361
01:10:20,596 --> 01:10:21,430
[explosions]

1362
01:10:21,889 --> 01:10:25,642
<i>A nation that had never murdered
<i>a single American citizen.</i></i>

1363
01:10:26,977 --> 01:10:30,772
[in Arabic] What's this baby's crime?
Was he going to fight the soldiers?

1364
01:10:30,939 --> 01:10:33,984
Cowards! I went out with a bat
and asked the soldier to hit me.

1365
01:10:34,151 --> 01:10:39,698
I swear on the Quran.
Those who don't fear death don't die.

1366
01:10:40,574 --> 01:10:43,869
[woman crying and wailing]

1367
01:10:44,036 --> 01:10:46,496
[indistinct chatter in Arabic]

1368
01:10:47,080 --> 01:10:52,628
Now, we're going to find this,
I think, piece of my neighbor, young girl.

1369
01:10:52,794 --> 01:10:54,838
Age twenty, Sham's.

1370
01:10:55,005 --> 01:10:58,884
I think is other part of her body.
That's all.

1371
01:10:59,051 --> 01:11:01,178
[men chat in Arabic]

1372
01:11:01,345 --> 01:11:04,223
There is a lot of innocent civilians
that were killed

1373
01:11:04,389 --> 01:11:07,476
<i>and I think
<i>that's because the U.S. Army,</i></i>

1374
01:11:07,643 --> 01:11:09,895
<i>you know, we came in,</i>

1375
01:11:10,062 --> 01:11:11,522
<i>and we knew it wasn't gonna be easy,</i>

1376
01:11:11,688 --> 01:11:14,191
and they pretty much at first,
shot anything that moved.

1377
01:11:14,358 --> 01:11:16,026
When war happens and the fighting starts,

1378
01:11:16,193 --> 01:11:19,029
you know, it's kinda like we're pumped up
and motivated and ready to go.

1379
01:11:19,196 --> 01:11:20,531
It's the ultimate rush.

1380
01:11:20,697 --> 01:11:23,158
'cause you know you're going
into the fight to begin with,

1381
01:11:23,325 --> 01:11:25,869
and then you got a good song playing
in the background,

1382
01:11:26,036 --> 01:11:30,249
and that's... That gets you
real fired up, ready to do the job.

1383
01:11:30,415 --> 01:11:34,002
You can hook your CD player to the tank's
internal communications system.

1384
01:11:34,169 --> 01:11:35,212
To the Charlie box.

1385
01:11:35,379 --> 01:11:37,798
So that way, when you put your helmet on,
you can hear it through it.

1386
01:11:37,965 --> 01:11:41,009
This is the one we listen to the most,
this is the one we travel

1387
01:11:41,176 --> 01:11:42,594
when we kill the enemy,

1388
01:11:42,761 --> 01:11:44,763
Drowning Pool's
"Let the Bodies Hit the Floor"

1389
01:11:44,930 --> 01:11:46,974
is just fitting for the job we were doing.

1390
01:11:47,140 --> 01:11:48,809
[Drowning Pool's<i>"Bodies" playing]</i>

1391
01:11:48,976 --> 01:11:50,185
[screaming]

1392
01:11:53,897 --> 01:11:56,942
"The Roof is on Fire",
because basically it symbolized

1393
01:11:57,109 --> 01:11:58,861
Baghdad being on fire

1394
01:11:59,027 --> 01:12:01,822
and at the time we wanted it to burn
to get Saddam and his regime out.

1395
01:12:01,989 --> 01:12:03,365
[explosion]

1396
01:12:03,532 --> 01:12:06,076
[soldier singing]
♪<i> The roof, the roof is on fire ♪</i>

1397
01:12:06,743 --> 01:12:10,247
♪<i> We don't need no water
<i>Let the motherfucker burn ♪</i></i>

1398
01:12:10,914 --> 01:12:13,417
♪<i> Burn, motherfucker, burn ♪</i>

1399
01:12:13,584 --> 01:12:17,880
[Rock Master Scott & the Dynamic Three's
"The Roof is on Fire" playing]

1400
01:12:18,589 --> 01:12:22,217
♪<i> Burn, motherfucker, burn ♪</i>

1401
01:12:24,595 --> 01:12:28,765
[soldier] <i>This is a whole totally
<i>different picture here, being pushed into</i></i>

1402
01:12:28,932 --> 01:12:30,976
the city, urban warfare in a tank,
you know!

1403
01:12:31,143 --> 01:12:33,270
-[loud engine]
-<i>Civilians!</i>

1404
01:12:34,229 --> 01:12:35,731
<i>Yeah, the civilians, it gets...</i>

1405
01:12:35,898 --> 01:12:37,983
<i>You don't know who's friendly,
<i>who's enemy.</i></i>

1406
01:12:38,358 --> 01:12:41,570
[soldier] <i>This was a lot more real
<i>and true than just a video game.</i></i>

1407
01:12:41,737 --> 01:12:44,698
A lot of people thought it was gonna be:
"Yeah, look through the sight and shoot!"

1408
01:12:44,865 --> 01:12:48,827
No, a lot of this is face to face,
and especially riding by

1409
01:12:48,994 --> 01:12:51,705
after the bombs that went off
and seeing all the people

1410
01:12:51,872 --> 01:12:54,458
<i>on the side of the road bloated up,
<i>and just...</i></i>

1411
01:12:54,625 --> 01:12:58,337
<i>all the smells around you, I mean,
<i>from the people lying dead and rotted.</i></i>

1412
01:12:58,504 --> 01:13:01,006
It's... It's a lot
more gruesome than you think.

1413
01:13:01,590 --> 01:13:04,510
[other soldier] <i>We called in with some
<i>artillery and napalm and things like that.</i></i>

1414
01:13:04,676 --> 01:13:06,637
<i>Some innocent women and children got hit.</i>

1415
01:13:07,054 --> 01:13:08,764
<i>We met them on the road and they had...</i>

1416
01:13:08,931 --> 01:13:11,558
I mean, little girls with noses blown off

1417
01:13:11,725 --> 01:13:16,230
and husbands carrying
their dead wives and things like that.

1418
01:13:16,396 --> 01:13:18,774
That was extremely difficult
to deal with 'cause you're like:

1419
01:13:18,941 --> 01:13:21,485
"Shoot, what the hell do we do now?"

1420
01:13:23,195 --> 01:13:26,031
The targeting capabilities
and the care that goes into targeting...

1421
01:13:26,198 --> 01:13:29,201
[explosion]

1422
01:13:29,952 --> 01:13:31,828
<i>-... is as impressive...
-[screaming]</i>

1423
01:13:31,995 --> 01:13:33,330
<i>...as anything, anyone could see.</i>

1424
01:13:33,497 --> 01:13:35,916
[automatic rifle shooting]

1425
01:13:36,083 --> 01:13:38,585
[soldier, through radio]
<i>Ah, erm... I get one! The other one!</i>

1426
01:13:38,752 --> 01:13:41,672
[automatic rifle shooting]

1427
01:13:41,839 --> 01:13:45,050
The care that goes into it,
the humanity that goes into it!

1428
01:13:45,217 --> 01:13:48,178
[in Arabic] They have no conscience!
They know nothing!

1429
01:13:48,345 --> 01:13:51,932
They slaughtered us!
They destroyed our houses!

1430
01:13:52,099 --> 01:13:55,060
God will destroy their houses!
God is great!

1431
01:13:55,227 --> 01:13:58,772
God will destroy their houses!
God is great!

1432
01:13:58,939 --> 01:14:01,316
God is great!
Victory to Iraq!

1433
01:14:01,483 --> 01:14:04,570
Victory to Iraq!
Victory to Iraq!

1434
01:14:04,736 --> 01:14:05,821
[crying]

1435
01:14:05,988 --> 01:14:08,031
[TV reporter, in Arabic]
You mean they killed civilians?

1436
01:14:08,198 --> 01:14:10,826
Yes, civilians! It's our uncle's house!

1437
01:14:10,993 --> 01:14:14,538
We're all civilians.
There is no militia here.

1438
01:14:15,122 --> 01:14:17,749
I pray to God to avenge us!
I can only count on you, God!

1439
01:14:17,916 --> 01:14:19,793
I can only count on you, God!

1440
01:14:19,960 --> 01:14:23,046
[crying]

1441
01:14:23,213 --> 01:14:25,799
We've had five funerals
because of the bombings.

1442
01:14:25,966 --> 01:14:28,844
Oh, God, oh, God, oh, God!

1443
01:14:29,011 --> 01:14:31,680
[crying]

1444
01:14:31,847 --> 01:14:33,849
Oh, God!

1445
01:14:34,016 --> 01:14:35,184
[crying]

1446
01:14:35,350 --> 01:14:36,727
God save us from them!

1447
01:14:36,894 --> 01:14:38,270
God, where are you?

1448
01:14:38,437 --> 01:14:40,189
Where are you?

1449
01:14:40,355 --> 01:14:42,191
[crying]

1450
01:14:42,357 --> 01:14:44,401
[chewing gum]

1451
01:14:44,568 --> 01:14:48,197
Honestly, I think we should just trust our
President in every decision that he makes

1452
01:14:48,363 --> 01:14:50,657
and we should just support that, you know,

1453
01:14:50,824 --> 01:14:53,368
and, um, be faithful in what happens.

1454
01:14:53,535 --> 01:14:55,412
-Do you trust this president?
-Yes, I do.

1455
01:14:55,579 --> 01:14:56,663
[clapping]

1456
01:14:57,539 --> 01:15:00,459
[Michael Moore]
<i>Britney Spears was not alone.</i>

1457
01:15:00,626 --> 01:15:04,630
<i>The majority of American people trusted
<i>the president, and why shouldn't they?</i></i>

1458
01:15:04,796 --> 01:15:05,797
[cheering]

1459
01:15:05,964 --> 01:15:10,052
<i>He had spent the better part of last year
<i>giving them every reason why</i></i>

1460
01:15:10,219 --> 01:15:12,012
<i>we should invade Iraq.</i>

1461
01:15:12,179 --> 01:15:17,434
Saddam Hussein has gone
to elaborate lengths, spent enormous sums,

1462
01:15:17,601 --> 01:15:21,897
taken great risks to build
and keep weapons of mass destruction.

1463
01:15:22,064 --> 01:15:26,109
Saddam Hussein is determined
to get his hands on a nuclear bomb

1464
01:15:26,276 --> 01:15:28,654
[repeats wrongly] "Nucular" weapon.

1465
01:15:28,820 --> 01:15:31,657
[Colin Powell]
<i>Active chemical munitions bunkers,</i>

1466
01:15:31,823 --> 01:15:33,534
mobile production facilities.

1467
01:15:33,700 --> 01:15:35,577
We know he's got chemical weapons.

1468
01:15:35,744 --> 01:15:37,746
[repeats] He's got them!

1469
01:15:38,205 --> 01:15:40,123
[Michael Moore]
<i>Huh, that's weird,</i>

1470
01:15:40,290 --> 01:15:43,669
<i>because that's not what Bush's people
<i>said when he first took office.</i></i>

1471
01:15:43,836 --> 01:15:47,005
He has not developed
any significant capability

1472
01:15:47,172 --> 01:15:48,924
with respect to weapons of mass
destruction.

1473
01:15:49,091 --> 01:15:52,553
He is unable to project
conventional power against his neighbors.

1474
01:15:52,719 --> 01:15:57,391
We are able to keep arms from him.
His military forces have not been rebuilt.

1475
01:15:57,558 --> 01:16:00,519
Saddam Hussein aids
and protects terrorists

1476
01:16:01,728 --> 01:16:03,856
including members of Al-Qaeda.

1477
01:16:04,022 --> 01:16:07,025
There was a relationship
between Iraq and Al-Qaeda.

1478
01:16:07,192 --> 01:16:09,528
[repeatedly alternates]
Saddam! Al-Qaeda!

1479
01:16:09,695 --> 01:16:11,196
Saddam! Al-Qaeda!

1480
01:16:11,363 --> 01:16:13,115
Saddam! Saddam! Al-Qaeda!

1481
01:16:13,282 --> 01:16:14,575
It is only a matter of time

1482
01:16:14,741 --> 01:16:18,078
before terrorist states armed
with weapons of mass destruction

1483
01:16:18,245 --> 01:16:21,582
develop the capability to deliver
those weapons to U.S. cities.

1484
01:16:21,748 --> 01:16:25,878
What we are giving you are facts and
conclusions based on solid intelligence.

1485
01:16:29,715 --> 01:16:31,216
The man who hates America.

1486
01:16:31,383 --> 01:16:34,261
This is a man who cannot stand
what we stand for.

1487
01:16:34,428 --> 01:16:37,848
His willingness to terrorize himself!

1488
01:16:38,015 --> 01:16:41,351
He hates the fact, like Al-Qaeda does,
that we love freedom.

1489
01:16:41,518 --> 01:16:44,438
After all, this is the guy that tried
to kill my dad at one time.

1490
01:16:44,605 --> 01:16:47,691
They simply got people to believe

1491
01:16:47,858 --> 01:16:51,236
that there was a real threat out there,
when in fact, there wasn't one.

1492
01:16:51,403 --> 01:16:54,072
You get told things every day
that don't happen,

1493
01:16:54,239 --> 01:16:55,824
it doesn't seem to bother people.

1494
01:16:55,991 --> 01:16:58,160
[Michael Moore]
<i>Of course, the Democrats were there</i>

1495
01:16:58,327 --> 01:17:00,120
<i>to put a stop to all these falsehoods.</i>

1496
01:17:00,287 --> 01:17:03,832
I will vote to give the president
the authority he needs.

1497
01:17:03,999 --> 01:17:05,751
The United States is prepared to lead

1498
01:17:05,918 --> 01:17:08,128
a coalition of the willing
that will do it.

1499
01:17:08,295 --> 01:17:10,797
When I say we will lead
a coalition of the willing

1500
01:17:10,964 --> 01:17:13,509
to disarm him if he chooses
not to disarm, I mean it.

1501
01:17:13,675 --> 01:17:15,594
Who is in that Coalition
of the Willing now, are...

1502
01:17:15,761 --> 01:17:17,429
You will find out who's in it.

1503
01:17:17,596 --> 01:17:18,889
[epic music]

1504
01:17:19,056 --> 01:17:21,725
[spoofing man voice]
<i>The Coalition of the Willing!</i>

1505
01:17:21,892 --> 01:17:25,854
<i>Roll call!
<i>The Republic of Palau.</i></i>

1506
01:17:26,021 --> 01:17:30,275
<i>The Republic of Costa Rica!</i>

1507
01:17:30,692 --> 01:17:34,196
<i>The Republic of Iceland!</i>

1508
01:17:34,363 --> 01:17:36,990
[Michael Moore]<i> Of course,
<i>none of these countries has an army,</i></i>

1509
01:17:37,157 --> 01:17:39,076
<i>or for that matter, weapons,</i>

1510
01:17:39,243 --> 01:17:42,454
<i>so it looked like we'd be doing
<i>most of the invading stuff ourselves.</i></i>

1511
01:17:42,621 --> 01:17:43,497
[horns ringing]

1512
01:17:43,664 --> 01:17:44,665
<i>Then, there was also...</i>

1513
01:17:44,831 --> 01:17:47,251
[spoofing voice] <i>Romania!</i>

1514
01:17:47,417 --> 01:17:51,505
<i>The Kingdom of Morocco!</i>

1515
01:17:52,548 --> 01:17:55,300
<i>Morocco wasn't officially
<i>a member of the coalition,</i></i>

1516
01:17:55,467 --> 01:17:57,302
<i>but according to one report,</i>

1517
01:17:57,469 --> 01:17:59,096
<i>they did offer
<i>to send 2,000 monkeys</i></i>

1518
01:17:59,263 --> 01:18:00,764
<i>to help detonate landmines.</i>

1519
01:18:00,931 --> 01:18:02,391
[monkeys screaming]

1520
01:18:02,558 --> 01:18:04,184
These are men of vision!

1521
01:18:04,351 --> 01:18:05,978
[spoofing voice] <i>The Netherlands!</i>

1522
01:18:06,144 --> 01:18:07,938
And I'm proud,
I'm proud to call them allies.

1523
01:18:08,105 --> 01:18:09,356
[monkeys screaming]

1524
01:18:09,523 --> 01:18:11,483
[spoofing voice] <i>Afghanistan!</i>

1525
01:18:12,109 --> 01:18:15,904
[Michael Moore]<i> Afghanistan?
<i>Oh, yeah, they had an army.</i></i>

1526
01:18:16,071 --> 01:18:17,281
<i>Our army!</i>

1527
01:18:18,073 --> 01:18:20,284
<i>I guess that's one way
<i>to build a coalition.</i></i>

1528
01:18:20,450 --> 01:18:22,619
<i>Just keep invading countries.</i>

1529
01:18:23,370 --> 01:18:26,164
<i>Yes, with our mighty coalition intact,</i>

1530
01:18:26,331 --> 01:18:27,416
<i>we were ready!</i>

1531
01:18:27,583 --> 01:18:28,834
[Donald Rumsfeld] <i>One could almost say</i>

1532
01:18:29,001 --> 01:18:30,794
it's the mother of all coalitions.

1533
01:18:30,961 --> 01:18:33,589
♪ <i>America ♪</i>

1534
01:18:33,755 --> 01:18:36,008
[Michael Moore]
<i>Fortunately, we have an independent media</i>

1535
01:18:36,175 --> 01:18:38,677
<i>in this country
<i>who would tell us the truth.</i></i>

1536
01:18:38,844 --> 01:18:41,763
The rallying around the president,
around the flag and around the troops

1537
01:18:41,930 --> 01:18:42,890
clearly has begun.

1538
01:18:43,056 --> 01:18:44,600
And we're gonna win!

1539
01:18:44,766 --> 01:18:47,352
You have to be with the troops
to understand the adrenaline they get.

1540
01:18:47,519 --> 01:18:49,980
I just want you to know,
I think Navy SEALS rock!

1541
01:18:50,147 --> 01:18:53,192
[CNN reporter]<i> The pictures you're seeing
<i>are absolutely phenomenal.</i></i>

1542
01:18:53,358 --> 01:18:57,863
When my country's at war,
I want my country to win.

1543
01:18:58,197 --> 01:19:01,575
Iraqi opposition has faded
in the face of American power.

1544
01:19:01,742 --> 01:19:03,452
[CNN reporter]<i> What you're watching</i>

1545
01:19:03,619 --> 01:19:06,121
<i>is truly historic television
<i>and journalism.</i></i>

1546
01:19:06,288 --> 01:19:07,831
[another CNN reporter]
<i>It was absolutely electrifying,</i>

1547
01:19:07,998 --> 01:19:11,293
<i>they actually had to strap me in
<i>with my camera at the back of the plane.</i></i>

1548
01:19:11,460 --> 01:19:13,837
An awesome synchronized killing machine.

1549
01:19:14,004 --> 01:19:18,383
There is an inherent bias in the coverage
of the American press in general.

1550
01:19:18,550 --> 01:19:20,969
Am I slanted and biased?
You damn well bet I am!

1551
01:19:21,136 --> 01:19:22,221
[loud firing]

1552
01:19:22,387 --> 01:19:23,805
-[explosion]
-[soldier] Yeah!

1553
01:19:23,972 --> 01:19:25,098
[soldier shouting]

1554
01:19:25,265 --> 01:19:29,978
[Michael Moore]<i> But one story the media
<i>wasn't covering was the personal story</i></i>

1555
01:19:30,145 --> 01:19:31,271
<i>of each and every soldier</i>

1556
01:19:31,438 --> 01:19:34,191
<i>who was killed in the war,</i>

1557
01:19:34,358 --> 01:19:36,151
<i>the government
<i>would not allow any cameras</i></i>

1558
01:19:36,318 --> 01:19:38,362
<i>to show the coffins coming home.</i>

1559
01:19:39,154 --> 01:19:41,114
<i>That kind of story is a downer.</i>

1560
01:19:41,281 --> 01:19:42,199
[classical music]

1561
01:19:42,366 --> 01:19:45,702
<i>Especially when you're getting ready
<i>for a party on a boat.</i></i>

1562
01:19:45,869 --> 01:19:49,289
[Joey Scarbury's
"Believe it or not" playing]

1563
01:19:49,456 --> 01:19:53,627
♪<i> I can't believe it myself ♪</i>

1564
01:19:54,211 --> 01:19:57,589
♪<i> Suddenly, I'm up on top of the world ♪</i>

1565
01:19:58,131 --> 01:20:01,802
♪<i> It should have been somebody else ♪</i>

1566
01:20:04,221 --> 01:20:08,350
♪<i> Believe it or not, I'm walking on air ♪</i>

1567
01:20:08,517 --> 01:20:11,895
♪<i> I never thought I could feel so free ♪</i>

1568
01:20:12,604 --> 01:20:16,483
♪<i> Flying away on a wing and a prayer ♪</i>

1569
01:20:16,650 --> 01:20:19,945
♪<i> Who could it be? ♪</i>

1570
01:20:20,654 --> 01:20:25,284
-♪<i> Believe it or not, it's just me ♪
-[cheering and clapping]</i>

1571
01:20:28,704 --> 01:20:30,873
[George W. Bush]
My fellow Americans,

1572
01:20:31,290 --> 01:20:34,459
major combat operations
in Iraq have ended.

1573
01:20:34,918 --> 01:20:40,632
In the battle of Iraq, the United States
and our allies have prevailed.

1574
01:20:40,799 --> 01:20:43,468
[cheering and clapping]

1575
01:20:45,512 --> 01:20:46,430
[explosion]

1576
01:20:46,597 --> 01:20:49,433
[bullets and sand tingling]

1577
01:20:49,600 --> 01:20:50,767
[soldier shouting]

1578
01:20:52,519 --> 01:20:54,980
[soldier] Get out of the way!

1579
01:20:55,147 --> 01:20:56,190
Move it! Move it!

1580
01:20:56,356 --> 01:21:00,360
[general chaos and shouting]

1581
01:21:01,862 --> 01:21:03,363
Move it! Move it! Move it!

1582
01:21:03,530 --> 01:21:06,450
[indistinct shouting throughout]

1583
01:21:12,706 --> 01:21:15,375
[shouting continues]

1584
01:21:21,298 --> 01:21:24,676
[tragic tune starts]

1585
01:21:24,843 --> 01:21:27,804
[female reporter] <i>One hundred sixty-two,
<i>the number of troops killed by bombing.</i></i>

1586
01:21:27,971 --> 01:21:29,389
[male reporter]
<i>Two hundred and forty-four U.S. troops.</i>

1587
01:21:29,556 --> 01:21:31,808
<i>Three hundred eighty-four U.S. troops
<i>have lost their lives.</i></i>

1588
01:21:31,975 --> 01:21:34,895
<i>-Total killed, 484.
<i>-Died on the line of duty, 500.</i></i>

1589
01:21:35,062 --> 01:21:36,522
[another reporter]<i> Six hundred
<i>and thirty-one American troops.</i></i>

1590
01:21:36,688 --> 01:21:38,774
[new reporter]<i> More than 825 troops
<i>have been killed in Iraq.</i></i>

1591
01:21:38,941 --> 01:21:41,944
<i>Largest number
<i>of American military deaths since Vietnam.</i></i>

1592
01:21:42,110 --> 01:21:45,364
There are some who feel like,
that, uh, if they...

1593
01:21:46,198 --> 01:21:50,285
attack us, that we may decide
to leave prematurely.

1594
01:21:51,745 --> 01:21:55,541
They don't understand what they're talking
about, if that's the case. Let me finish.

1595
01:21:56,124 --> 01:22:00,254
Um, there are some who,
uh, feel like that, you know,

1596
01:22:00,420 --> 01:22:03,215
the conditions are such
that they can attack us there.

1597
01:22:03,382 --> 01:22:04,925
My answer is: "Bring 'em on!"

1598
01:22:05,509 --> 01:22:07,845
[crowd shouting]

1599
01:22:08,011 --> 01:22:10,097
-[sirens ringing]
-[crowd shouting]

1600
01:22:12,599 --> 01:22:14,935
[thudding]

1601
01:22:16,270 --> 01:22:18,438
-[shouting]
-[honking]

1602
01:22:18,981 --> 01:22:20,482
The United States were just planning on,

1603
01:22:20,649 --> 01:22:21,817
just walking through here

1604
01:22:21,984 --> 01:22:24,403
like it was going to be easy and all,

1605
01:22:24,570 --> 01:22:27,573
it's not that easy
to conquer a country, is it? Huh!

1606
01:22:27,739 --> 01:22:31,743
-[tambourine]
-[crowd chanting in Arabic]

1607
01:22:31,910 --> 01:22:34,329
[rock music playing]

1608
01:22:34,496 --> 01:22:36,415
[Dan Rather]
<i>The renewed battle for control of Iraq</i>

1609
01:22:36,582 --> 01:22:38,375
raged for a fourth day today,

1610
01:22:38,542 --> 01:22:40,752
with street clashes
in nearly every corner of the country,

1611
01:22:42,087 --> 01:22:44,548
Iraq could become,
quote, "Another Vietnam".

1612
01:22:44,715 --> 01:22:46,592
[reporter]<i> Officials say they see evidence</i>

1613
01:22:46,758 --> 01:22:49,803
<i>that Sunni and Shia extremists
<i>might be joining forces.</i></i>

1614
01:22:49,970 --> 01:22:51,930
They're not happy they're occupied.

1615
01:22:53,182 --> 01:22:55,350
But I wouldn't be happy
if I were occupied either.

1616
01:22:55,517 --> 01:22:57,811
[Bloodhound Gang's
"Fire Water Burn" playing]

1617
01:22:57,978 --> 01:23:01,231
♪<i> C'mon, party people
<i>Put your hands in the air ♪</i></i>

1618
01:23:01,398 --> 01:23:02,608
[cheering]

1619
01:23:02,774 --> 01:23:04,067
♪<i> C'mon, party people ♪</i>

1620
01:23:04,234 --> 01:23:05,652
[screaming]

1621
01:23:05,819 --> 01:23:08,780
[news anchor]<i> Two Japanese aid workers
<i>and a journalist kidnapped by men</i></i>

1622
01:23:08,947 --> 01:23:12,034
<i>calling themselves
<i>the Mujahedeen Squadrons.</i></i>

1623
01:23:12,201 --> 01:23:14,119
<i>They've threatened to burn
<i>their hostages alive</i></i>

1624
01:23:14,870 --> 01:23:18,540
<i>if Japan does not withdraw its troops
<i>from Iraq within three days.</i></i>

1625
01:23:19,333 --> 01:23:20,709
[TV reporter] What's happened?

1626
01:23:20,876 --> 01:23:23,128
-[masked man] Uh, oh!
-They attacked our convoy.

1627
01:23:23,295 --> 01:23:24,338
[translates into Arabic]

1628
01:23:25,047 --> 01:23:25,923
[dialogues in Arabic]

1629
01:23:26,089 --> 01:23:28,091
-[reporter] Wanna give us your name?
-Hamilton.

1630
01:23:28,258 --> 01:23:30,636
-[dialogues in Arabic]
-Thomas!

1631
01:23:30,802 --> 01:23:33,722
[news anchor]<i> The Pentagon
<i>might keep up to 24,000 troops</i></i>

1632
01:23:33,889 --> 01:23:35,516
<i>in combat beyond their tour.</i>

1633
01:23:35,682 --> 01:23:38,018
I know our numbers
in the military have gone down.

1634
01:23:38,185 --> 01:23:39,603
<i>They talk about retention.</i>

1635
01:23:40,312 --> 01:23:41,939
[another soldier]
<i>Yeah, I never expected</i>

1636
01:23:42,105 --> 01:23:45,192
to be deployed this long,
I don't think anybody did.

1637
01:23:45,734 --> 01:23:48,403
I don't have any clue
as to why we're still in Iraq.

1638
01:23:48,570 --> 01:23:51,949
If Donald Rumsfeld was here,
I'd ask him for his resignation.

1639
01:23:52,115 --> 01:23:53,158
[shouting in background]

1640
01:23:53,325 --> 01:23:55,202
[Michael Moore]
<i>With the war not going as planned</i>

1641
01:23:55,827 --> 01:23:58,580
<i>and the military in need
<i>of many more troops...</i></i>

1642
01:23:59,623 --> 01:24:01,834
<i>where would they find the new recruits?</i>

1643
01:24:02,000 --> 01:24:04,002
[news anchor]
<i>Military experts say three times</i>

1644
01:24:04,169 --> 01:24:07,756
<i>the 120,000 U.S. troops now deployed
<i>would be needed</i></i>

1645
01:24:07,923 --> 01:24:10,050
<i>to pacify and rebuild the country.</i>

1646
01:24:10,217 --> 01:24:11,468
[car rolling]

1647
01:24:11,635 --> 01:24:14,471
[Michael Moore]
<i>They would find them all across America</i>

1648
01:24:15,097 --> 01:24:18,350
<i>in the places that had been
<i>destroyed by the economy.</i></i>

1649
01:24:18,976 --> 01:24:23,522
<i>Places where one of the only jobs
<i>available was to join the army.</i></i>

1650
01:24:23,689 --> 01:24:26,775
<i>Places like my hometown of Flint,
<i>Michigan.</i></i>

1651
01:24:26,942 --> 01:24:28,610
[Torian Billings]
<i>I was watching TV one day,</i>

1652
01:24:28,777 --> 01:24:31,655
and they showed some of the buildings
and areas that had been hit by bombs

1653
01:24:31,822 --> 01:24:35,200
and things like that,
and while watching, I got to thinking,

1654
01:24:35,367 --> 01:24:39,037
parts of Flint look like that
and we ain't been in a war.

1655
01:24:39,830 --> 01:24:41,748
[Gregory Fitch]
Look at the neighborhood I live in!

1656
01:24:41,915 --> 01:24:43,208
Most of them are abandoned.

1657
01:24:43,375 --> 01:24:46,837
I mean, you know, that's not right,
you want to talk about terrorism?

1658
01:24:47,004 --> 01:24:50,048
Come right here, president Bush,
right here! Come right here!

1659
01:24:50,674 --> 01:24:53,051
He knows about this corner, I emailed him.

1660
01:24:53,760 --> 01:24:56,388
At the end of January of '04,

1661
01:24:56,555 --> 01:24:59,141
the unemployment rate in Flint
was actually 17%,

1662
01:24:59,308 --> 01:25:02,060
<i>but you have
<i>to take into consideration as well</i></i>

1663
01:25:02,227 --> 01:25:05,189
<i>that when your unemployment runs out,
<i>you're no longer counted.</i></i>

1664
01:25:05,355 --> 01:25:10,068
<i>I would say that we're probably close
<i>to at least 50%, not working</i></i>

1665
01:25:10,235 --> 01:25:11,695
or under-employed.

1666
01:25:11,862 --> 01:25:14,364
Because being under-employed
is just as dangerous.

1667
01:25:15,157 --> 01:25:17,659
So my family has gone through
the welfare system,

1668
01:25:17,826 --> 01:25:19,912
when it was Jobs Central, in the mid-80s,

1669
01:25:20,078 --> 01:25:23,207
I came through the job training
partnership program,

1670
01:25:23,373 --> 01:25:24,458
here at Jobs Central,

1671
01:25:24,625 --> 01:25:26,168
and I went to a secretary school.

1672
01:25:26,919 --> 01:25:30,547
Years later, I'm the executive assistant
to the president of the agency.

1673
01:25:30,714 --> 01:25:32,090
Interesting! [laughing]

1674
01:25:32,257 --> 01:25:34,259
<i>My mother used to tell me
<i>all the time that:</i></i>

1675
01:25:34,426 --> 01:25:36,678
<i>"Why do you always go for the underdog?"</i>

1676
01:25:36,845 --> 01:25:39,139
<i>It was because the underdog is
<i>who needed me.</i></i>

1677
01:25:39,306 --> 01:25:42,601
<i>People that don't have anything,
<i>that's who I have to fight for.</i></i>

1678
01:25:42,768 --> 01:25:44,895
<i>And that's who I have fought for
<i>my entire life.</i></i>

1679
01:25:45,437 --> 01:25:48,273
I started taking my children,
and telling my children:

1680
01:25:48,440 --> 01:25:51,777
"The military is a good option,
I can't afford to have you go to college,

1681
01:25:51,944 --> 01:25:54,571
I cannot pay your way.
Financial aid will not help you."

1682
01:25:54,738 --> 01:25:57,407
So, I, as a mother,
started teaching my children

1683
01:25:57,574 --> 01:25:59,785
about the options
that the military could do.

1684
01:25:59,952 --> 01:26:02,955
That would take them around the world,
they would see all the things that I,

1685
01:26:03,121 --> 01:26:05,958
as a mother, could not let them see,
it would pay for their education

1686
01:26:06,124 --> 01:26:09,002
that I, as their mother,
and their father, could not pay for.

1687
01:26:09,419 --> 01:26:11,922
[Michael Moore] The military's
a good option for kids in Flint?

1688
01:26:12,089 --> 01:26:14,842
Military's an excellent option
for the people in the city of Flint.

1689
01:26:16,677 --> 01:26:20,055
[Michael Moore] How many have a friend
or a family member in the service?

1690
01:26:21,932 --> 01:26:24,351
Anybody currently serving overseas?

1691
01:26:24,518 --> 01:26:26,311
-Brother of mine.
-My cousin.

1692
01:26:26,478 --> 01:26:27,729
Yeah, a cousin.

1693
01:26:27,896 --> 01:26:29,773
-[Michael Moore] Where is your brother?
-Iraq.

1694
01:26:29,940 --> 01:26:31,233
Germany!

1695
01:26:31,942 --> 01:26:35,612
My cousin got shipped off to Iraq,
like, three days ago.

1696
01:26:36,321 --> 01:26:37,447
[Michael Moore] Alright!

1697
01:26:37,865 --> 01:26:41,118
There's, like, an army
or Navy recruiter or Marines recruiter

1698
01:26:41,285 --> 01:26:43,328
up there almost every week.

1699
01:26:44,037 --> 01:26:48,166
He's in the lunch room
recruiting students from the lunch room!

1700
01:26:49,001 --> 01:26:51,336
[dramatic male voice]
<i>There are people with a calling.</i>

1701
01:26:51,503 --> 01:26:55,966
[heroic music]

1702
01:26:56,133 --> 01:26:57,759
<i>Most serve one weekend a month</i>

1703
01:26:57,926 --> 01:26:59,761
<i>and two weeks a year.</i>

1704
01:26:59,928 --> 01:27:01,680
[heroic music intensifies]

1705
01:27:01,847 --> 01:27:03,432
<i>Earning money for college.</i>

1706
01:27:03,599 --> 01:27:06,310
[throbbing of rotor blades]

1707
01:27:07,394 --> 01:27:09,229
<i>Protecting their community.</i>

1708
01:27:10,981 --> 01:27:14,610
<i>In the Army National Guard, you can!</i>

1709
01:27:14,776 --> 01:27:17,946
[music ends dramatically]

1710
01:27:18,113 --> 01:27:19,615
I'm going into the Air Force myself.

1711
01:27:19,781 --> 01:27:22,784
I'm going to take a year off,
probably after high school,

1712
01:27:22,951 --> 01:27:26,246
and then make a career, I want to be
an aircraft maintenance technician.

1713
01:27:26,413 --> 01:27:29,583
I ran into a recruiter and, uh,
there was something I noticed about it,

1714
01:27:29,750 --> 01:27:32,294
and this is kinda on another...
I noticed it was odd.

1715
01:27:32,461 --> 01:27:35,005
It was more like he was hiring me
for a job than recruiting me for the Army.

1716
01:27:35,172 --> 01:27:36,423
It was the way he approached me,

1717
01:27:36,590 --> 01:27:37,758
<i>he approached a friend of mine.</i>

1718
01:27:37,925 --> 01:27:40,093
<i>I was in Borders Books and Music,
<i>he just came up,</i></i>

1719
01:27:40,260 --> 01:27:41,553
he handed us a business card.

1720
01:27:41,720 --> 01:27:43,639
They have business cards
made for the Army.

1721
01:27:43,805 --> 01:27:49,061
[funky tune]

1722
01:27:49,228 --> 01:27:51,688
[Michael Moore]
<i>Meet Marine Staff Sergeant Dale Kortman</i>

1723
01:27:51,855 --> 01:27:53,774
<i>and Sergeant Raymond Plouhar.</i>

1724
01:27:55,108 --> 01:27:58,445
<i>They are two of the many recruiters
<i>assigned to Flint, Michigan.</i></i>

1725
01:27:59,488 --> 01:28:01,615
<i>They're very busy these days.</i>

1726
01:28:01,782 --> 01:28:03,784
[Plouhar]
Look it, he's running away already.

1727
01:28:03,951 --> 01:28:05,285
He's seen us coming.

1728
01:28:05,452 --> 01:28:06,703
[Kortman] Yeah!

1729
01:28:07,329 --> 01:28:09,790
What we got here?
It's like a little gangster!

1730
01:28:09,957 --> 01:28:11,208
[Plouhar] Yeah!

1731
01:28:11,959 --> 01:28:14,044
[Kortman] We're heading over
to the Courtland mall right now.

1732
01:28:15,963 --> 01:28:19,132
[Michael Moore]<i> They decided not to go
<i>to the wealthier Genesee Valley mall</i></i>

1733
01:28:19,299 --> 01:28:23,345
<i>in the suburbs, they have a hard time
<i>recruiting young people there.</i></i>

1734
01:28:23,512 --> 01:28:26,515
<i>Instead, they went to the other mall.</i>

1735
01:28:26,849 --> 01:28:28,809
[Kortman]
Let's go in through Mervyns.

1736
