01:38:18,815 --> 01:38:20,192
You know, you, you...

1956
01:38:20,359 --> 01:38:27,366
I feel that a part of your soul...
is destroyed in taking another life.

1957
01:38:28,617 --> 01:38:31,370
And, yes, that statement is very true,
you...

1958
01:38:32,454 --> 01:38:35,249
cannot kill someone
without killing a part of yourself.

1959
01:38:36,208 --> 01:38:38,418
[Michael Moore] If you get called up,
would you go back to Iraq?

1960
01:38:38,585 --> 01:38:39,670
No.

1961
01:38:39,837 --> 01:38:41,129
-You're not?
-No!

1962
01:38:41,588 --> 01:38:44,925
[Michael Moore] What repercussions
do you face, if you don't?

1963
01:38:45,092 --> 01:38:48,262
It's possible jail time,
that's one possibility.

1964
01:38:48,428 --> 01:38:49,555
Are you willing to risk that?

1965
01:38:49,721 --> 01:38:52,140
Yes. Yes, I...

1966
01:38:53,100 --> 01:38:55,769
I will not let my person...

1967
01:38:58,188 --> 01:39:00,899
I will not let anyone

1968
01:39:01,567 --> 01:39:04,987
send me back over there
to kill other poor people.

1969
01:39:05,153 --> 01:39:10,117
especially when they pose no threat
to me and my country.

1970
01:39:14,955 --> 01:39:16,206
I won't do it.

1971
01:39:17,583 --> 01:39:21,545
This is an impressive crowd:
the haves, and the have-mores.

1972
01:39:21,712 --> 01:39:24,506
[crowd laughing]

1973
01:39:24,673 --> 01:39:26,717
Some people call you the elite.

1974
01:39:27,134 --> 01:39:28,385
I call you my base.

1975
01:39:28,552 --> 01:39:32,514
[crowd laughing and clapping]

1976
01:39:32,681 --> 01:39:35,809
[crowd cheering and whistling]

1977
01:39:35,976 --> 01:39:36,977
[military music]

1978
01:39:37,144 --> 01:39:39,688
[Michael Moore]<i> While Bush
<i>was busy taking care of his base</i></i>

1979
01:39:39,855 --> 01:39:42,024
<i>and professing his love for our troops,</i>

1980
01:39:42,191 --> 01:39:45,527
<i>he proposed cutting
<i>combat soldiers' pay by 33%.</i></i>

1981
01:39:45,694 --> 01:39:46,695
[clapping]

1982
01:39:46,862 --> 01:39:49,239
<i>And assistance to their families by 60%.</i>

1983
01:39:50,032 --> 01:39:52,618
<i>He opposed giving veterans
<i>a billion dollars more</i></i>

1984
01:39:52,784 --> 01:39:54,161
<i>in healthcare benefits.</i>

1985
01:39:54,912 --> 01:39:57,623
<i>And he supported
<i>closing veteran hospitals.</i></i>

1986
01:39:58,081 --> 01:40:00,792
<i>He tried to double
<i>the prescription drug costs for veterans</i></i>

1987
01:40:01,668 --> 01:40:04,713
<i>and opposed full benefits
<i>for part-time reservists.</i></i>

1988
01:40:04,880 --> 01:40:06,507
[crowds applauding]

1989
01:40:06,673 --> 01:40:11,261
<i>And when staff Sergeant Brett Petriken
<i>from Flint was killed in Iraq on May 26,</i></i>

1990
01:40:11,428 --> 01:40:14,014
<i>the Army sent
<i>his last paycheck to his family,</i></i>

1991
01:40:14,181 --> 01:40:17,809
<i>but they docked him for the last five days
<i>of the month that he didn't work</i></i>

1992
01:40:17,976 --> 01:40:19,353
<i>because he was dead.</i>

1993
01:40:21,438 --> 01:40:24,525
They say they're not going to leave
any veteran behind, but they're leaving

1994
01:40:24,691 --> 01:40:27,027
<i>all kinds of veterans behind.</i>

1995
01:40:27,194 --> 01:40:30,822
To say that we're forgotten, no,
I know we're not forgotten, but missed?

1996
01:40:30,989 --> 01:40:34,493
Yes. Yes. You know, there are
a lot of soldiers that have been missed,

1997
01:40:34,660 --> 01:40:36,203
that have been skipped over,

1998
01:40:36,370 --> 01:40:38,914
that didn't get the proper coverage
that they deserved.

1999
01:40:39,081 --> 01:40:42,125
They have a death toll, but they're not
showing the amount of people

2000
01:40:42,292 --> 01:40:44,837
that have been injured or are amputated
because of their injuries, you know.

2001
01:40:45,587 --> 01:40:47,965
-Like, I still feel like I have hands.
-[Brian Williams] Yeah!

2002
01:40:48,131 --> 01:40:52,469
And the pain is like,
my hands are being crushed in a vice.

2003
01:40:52,636 --> 01:40:56,431
But they do a lot to help it,
and they take a lot of the edge off it,

2004
01:40:56,598 --> 01:40:59,351
and it makes it
a lot more tolerable and...

2005
01:40:59,977 --> 01:41:02,646
[soldier] <i>I was injured in late April,
<i>on patrol in Baghdad.</i></i>

2006
01:41:03,564 --> 01:41:06,817
Um... [sniffles]
a couple of guys came out.

2007
01:41:07,568 --> 01:41:09,152
Ambushed us.

2008
01:41:09,319 --> 01:41:13,866
I've got nerve damage and stuff like that,
and I've got a lot of pain,

2009
01:41:14,032 --> 01:41:15,784
I'm constantly in pain.

2010
01:41:16,451 --> 01:41:21,999
Um, I take a lot of morphine
to help with that stuff.

2011
01:41:23,458 --> 01:41:27,421
I'm doing... you know, just readjusting,

2012
01:41:27,588 --> 01:41:31,133
getting life back on track.

2013
01:41:31,300 --> 01:41:32,801
You know what I'm saying?

2014
01:41:32,968 --> 01:41:37,055
Yes. I'm not gonna do
what it is that I did before.

2015
01:41:37,639 --> 01:41:41,435
Um, I... I was a Republican
for quite a few years.

2016
01:41:41,602 --> 01:41:43,270
And, um...

2017
01:41:44,229 --> 01:41:46,690
For some reason, they...

2018
01:41:49,818 --> 01:41:52,362
They conduct business
in a very dishonest way.

2019
01:41:52,529 --> 01:41:53,822
I'm gonna be incredibly active

2020
01:41:53,989 --> 01:41:57,576
in the Democratic party
down where I live once I get out.

2021
01:41:57,743 --> 01:42:03,457
So, I'm gonna definitely do my best
to ensure that the Democrats win control.

2022
01:42:04,291 --> 01:42:07,961
Iraq, Baghdad, I didn't know
anything of those things.

2023
01:42:09,505 --> 01:42:12,758
And we were in the hallway
in the upstairs of our house,

2024
01:42:12,925 --> 01:42:15,177
<i>and he was crying,</i>

2025
01:42:15,344 --> 01:42:20,432
<i>he said that he was really scared
<i>and he didn't want to have to go to Iraq.</i></i>

2026
01:42:20,599 --> 01:42:24,144
We were able to have a whole conversation
about sometimes some fear is healthy,

2027
01:42:24,311 --> 01:42:26,230
because it keeps our senses about us.

2028
01:42:26,396 --> 01:42:29,483
<i>And that's when he told me that
<i>he had not told anybody else but he knew</i></i>

2029
01:42:29,650 --> 01:42:31,109
<i>he was going to Baghdad.</i>

2030
01:42:31,276 --> 01:42:33,237
-[Michael Moore] Wow!
-[baby crying]

2031
01:42:33,779 --> 01:42:37,324
As everybody,
we were glued to the TV.

2032
01:42:37,783 --> 01:42:41,245
Just glued, completely glued
to the television,

2033
01:42:41,411 --> 01:42:42,829
in hopes of seeing a glimpse of him.

2034
01:42:42,996 --> 01:42:45,082
"Can't you please go
to where the helicopters are,

2035
01:42:45,249 --> 01:42:47,459
can't you please let us see him?"

2036
01:42:47,626 --> 01:42:50,295
Then, that night,
it was about ten something,

2037
01:42:50,462 --> 01:42:52,840
I went upstairs to the bedroom,

2038
01:42:53,006 --> 01:42:56,677
I was lying in bed and I was flipping
the channels, all I heard was:

2039
01:42:56,844 --> 01:42:59,221
"Black Hawk down, South Central Iraq."

2040
01:42:59,638 --> 01:43:03,851
<i>All I can tell you at this hour is that
<i>last night the Army did indeed lose</i></i>

2041
01:43:04,017 --> 01:43:05,978
<i>a Black Hawk helicopter.</i>

2042
01:43:06,144 --> 01:43:08,480
<i>We are being told
<i>by officers on the ground</i></i>

2043
01:43:08,647 --> 01:43:11,358
<i>that there were six occupants
<i>inside the Black Hawk.</i></i>

2044
01:43:11,525 --> 01:43:14,027
[Lila Lipscomb] The next morning,
I got up and I said:

2045
01:43:14,194 --> 01:43:16,154
"You push those thoughts
out of your mind!

2046
01:43:16,321 --> 01:43:18,240
OK Jesus, I need you to come in,

2047
01:43:18,407 --> 01:43:20,367
I need you Jesus,
you gotta help me through this!"

2048
01:43:20,951 --> 01:43:22,202
The army called me,

2049
01:43:22,369 --> 01:43:26,874
I remember getting on the phone
and him asking me if I was Lila Lipscomb.

2050
01:43:27,040 --> 01:43:30,419
I said yes and he said:
"Mother of Sergeant Michael Pedersen?"

2051
01:43:32,588 --> 01:43:34,965
[voice shaking]
And I remember dropping the telephone.

2052
01:43:37,634 --> 01:43:38,635
[sniffling]

2053
01:43:38,802 --> 01:43:41,763
And all I can honestly say
that I remember is:

2054
01:43:41,930 --> 01:43:42,848
"Ma'am!

2055
01:43:43,015 --> 01:43:48,020
The United States Army, the Secretary
of Defense regretfully informs you..."

2056
01:43:50,606 --> 01:43:51,523
That's all I know.

2057
01:43:53,942 --> 01:43:57,237
The grief grabbed me so hard

2058
01:43:57,905 --> 01:44:00,449
that I literally fell on the floor.

2059
01:44:00,616 --> 01:44:03,619
And I was alone,
I didn't have anybody to pick me up.

2060
01:44:04,119 --> 01:44:07,664
So I literally crawled over to my desk,

2061
01:44:08,040 --> 01:44:11,585
and was hanging on,
and I remember screaming:

2062
01:44:12,127 --> 01:44:16,215
"Why does it have to be Michael?
Why did you have to take my son?

2063
01:44:16,715 --> 01:44:21,386
Why is it my son that you had to take?
He didn't do anything!

2064
01:44:21,845 --> 01:44:26,725
He wasn't a bad guy, he was a good guy,
why did you have to take my son?"

2065
01:44:26,892 --> 01:44:28,727
Uh, I, erm...

2066
01:44:28,894 --> 01:44:30,896
[stutters]

2067
01:44:31,063 --> 01:44:33,899
I can't imagine what it must be like
to lose a son or a daughter,

2068
01:44:34,066 --> 01:44:38,487
or a husband or a wife,
and I... it pains me.

2069
01:44:39,488 --> 01:44:40,739
[paper crumpling]

2070
01:44:40,906 --> 01:44:42,533
[Michael Moore]
You have his last letter?

2071
01:44:43,116 --> 01:44:44,826
And it was mailed March 16th

2072
01:44:45,619 --> 01:44:48,956
but I didn't get it until
about a week before he was killed.

2073
01:44:50,207 --> 01:44:55,254
"Hello. Hey mama, well,
sorry I haven't been able to call,

2074
01:44:55,420 --> 01:44:59,800
they took the phones seven days ago,
I got the letter and box,

2075
01:44:59,967 --> 01:45:03,095
that is so cool,
your first grandson came...

2076
01:45:03,262 --> 01:45:05,055
[heavy breathing]

2077
01:45:05,222 --> 01:45:07,850
... the same day your oldest son did.

2078
01:45:08,016 --> 01:45:10,394
How is everyone? I'm doing fine.

2079
01:45:10,561 --> 01:45:14,731
We are just out here in the sand
and windstorms, waiting.

2080
01:45:14,898 --> 01:45:20,654
What in the world is wrong with George
'trying to be like his dad' Bush?

2081
01:45:20,821 --> 01:45:23,699
He got us out here for nothing whatsoever.

2082
01:45:23,866 --> 01:45:26,660
I am so furious right now, Mama.

2083
01:45:27,870 --> 01:45:32,541
I really hope they do not
re-elect that fool, honestly.

2084
01:45:33,208 --> 01:45:36,003
I am in good spirits and I am doing OK.

2085
01:45:36,170 --> 01:45:37,880
I really miss you guys.

2086
01:45:38,046 --> 01:45:39,173
Thanks for the Bible...

2087
01:45:39,339 --> 01:45:41,592
[repressing tears]

2088
01:45:41,758 --> 01:45:44,261
... and books, and candy.

2089
01:45:44,428 --> 01:45:47,264
[voice shaking] I really look forward
to letters from you guys.

2090
01:45:48,849 --> 01:45:50,767
Well, tell all the family hello

2091
01:45:51,393 --> 01:45:53,145
and that I am doing fine.

2092
01:45:53,312 --> 01:45:56,732
We don't expect
anything to happen any time soon.

2093
01:45:56,899 --> 01:46:00,777
I cannot wait to get home
and get back to my life.

2094
01:46:01,278 --> 01:46:03,155
Tell Sputnik congrats.

2095
01:46:03,530 --> 01:46:06,617
And I'll see my first nephew soon,

2096
01:46:07,993 --> 01:46:10,078
as soon as I get back to the States.

2097
01:46:10,746 --> 01:46:13,040
Hope you guys are doing OK

2098
01:46:13,207 --> 01:46:15,167
and keep sending the mail.

2099
01:46:15,334 --> 01:46:18,045
It makes getting through the days easier.

2100
01:46:20,047 --> 01:46:21,131
[gulping]

2101
01:46:21,298 --> 01:46:27,095
Well, I am on my way to bed,
so I will write you guys soon.

2102
01:46:28,180 --> 01:46:31,475
[sobbing]
I love and miss all of you guys."

2103
01:46:33,185 --> 01:46:35,145
-"Love, Michael."
-[paper flapping]

2104
01:46:44,988 --> 01:46:46,823
I want him to be alive,

2105
01:46:47,533 --> 01:46:49,576
and I can't make him alive.

2106
01:46:49,743 --> 01:46:51,078
[sniffling]

2107
01:46:51,245 --> 01:46:53,372
But your flesh just aches.

2108
01:46:54,373 --> 01:46:56,834
You want your child, it's out of sync.

2109
01:46:57,000 --> 01:47:00,838
A parent is not supposed
to bury their child.

2110
01:47:01,004 --> 01:47:03,590
[Lila sobbing]

2111
01:47:03,757 --> 01:47:07,636
[Howard Lipscomb]
<i>I feel, I... I... I feel sad for my family</i>

2112
01:47:07,803 --> 01:47:10,013
<i>because we lost our son.</i>

2113
01:47:11,557 --> 01:47:12,641
But...

2114
01:47:13,517 --> 01:47:16,645
I really feel sorry
for the other families

2115
01:47:16,812 --> 01:47:21,066
that is losing their kids as we speak.

2116
01:47:24,069 --> 01:47:25,612
And for what?

2117
01:47:25,779 --> 01:47:27,364
I don't...

2118
01:47:29,074 --> 01:47:33,203
That's the, I guess, sickening part.
For what?

2119
01:47:33,954 --> 01:47:35,956
You've heard a lot
about Halliburton lately.

2120
01:47:36,123 --> 01:47:41,086
Criticism is okay. We can take it.
Criticism is not failure.

2121
01:47:41,253 --> 01:47:43,422
Our employees are doing a great job.

2122
01:47:43,589 --> 01:47:46,717
<i>We're feeding the soldiers,
<i>we're rebuilding Iraq.</i></i>

2123
01:47:46,884 --> 01:47:50,012
Will things go wrong?
Sure they will, it's a war zone.

2124
01:47:50,179 --> 01:47:52,806
We're serving the troops
because of what we know,

2125
01:47:52,973 --> 01:47:54,266
not who we know.

2126
01:47:54,433 --> 01:47:57,519
Well, let me tell you about Halliburton,
the company I ran.

2127
01:47:57,686 --> 01:47:59,521
I'm very proud of what I did
at Halliburton,

2128
01:47:59,688 --> 01:48:02,566
the people of Halliburton are very proud
of what they've accomplished

2129
01:48:02,733 --> 01:48:04,276
and I frankly

2130
01:48:04,776 --> 01:48:08,113
don't feel any need to apologize
for the way I've spent my time

2131
01:48:08,280 --> 01:48:11,074
over the last five years
as the C.E.O. and Chairman

2132
01:48:11,241 --> 01:48:12,951
of a major American corporation,
a good one.

2133
01:48:13,118 --> 01:48:16,121
This is also an attempt
to divert attention away from the fact

2134
01:48:16,288 --> 01:48:17,748
they have no energy policy.

2135
01:48:18,916 --> 01:48:22,002
And as the Secretary of Energy said,
we were caught unawares!

2136
01:48:22,169 --> 01:48:24,296
[Caribbean music]

2137
01:48:24,463 --> 01:48:26,590
[Michael Moore]
<i>In the middle of the war, Microsoft,</i>

2138
01:48:26,757 --> 01:48:30,052
<i>DHL and other corporations
<i>invited Halliburton</i></i>

2139
01:48:30,219 --> 01:48:31,720
<i>to a conference</i>

2140
01:48:31,887 --> 01:48:34,765
<i>to figure out how much money
<i>could be made in Iraq.</i></i>

2141
01:48:36,350 --> 01:48:37,601
[Michael Mele]
<i>Having worked</i>

2142
01:48:37,768 --> 01:48:44,691
this, uh... effort
even since before the invasion,

2143
01:48:44,858 --> 01:48:47,152
the, uh, liberation of Iraq started.

2144
01:48:47,319 --> 01:48:52,157
You, industry, are definitely
a vital part of that effort.

2145
01:48:52,324 --> 01:48:55,410
We appreciate your interest in this.
We need you.

2146
01:48:55,577 --> 01:48:58,455
Now, lots of you are
small businesses and you are struggling.

2147
01:48:58,622 --> 01:49:00,457
How do we get a piece of this big action?

2148
01:49:00,624 --> 01:49:02,876
All of you, the big guys,
are going to get it and the rest of us

2149
01:49:03,043 --> 01:49:05,921
that have subcontracting capability,
or no, none at all.

2150
01:49:06,088 --> 01:49:08,549
U.S.T.V.A. is for you.

2151
01:49:08,715 --> 01:49:10,884
Once that oil start flowing
and money coming,

2152
01:49:11,051 --> 01:49:12,845
it's going to be lots of money,

2153
01:49:13,011 --> 01:49:15,138
it's the second largest oil reserve
in the world.

2154
01:49:15,305 --> 01:49:16,974
There's no question
about how much money is there.

2155
01:49:17,140 --> 01:49:21,603
I've been getting complaints
from Iraqi firms and from American firms,

2156
01:49:21,770 --> 01:49:24,690
that the lack of transparency,
the corruption...

2157
01:49:24,857 --> 01:49:27,276
I think the profits
that American companies are making,

2158
01:49:27,442 --> 01:49:29,111
the majors, the main companies,

2159
01:49:29,278 --> 01:49:31,238
are so overwhelming,

2160
01:49:31,405 --> 01:49:34,783
I mean, like when you have a line item
for a million dollars

2161
01:49:34,950 --> 01:49:38,245
and you subcontract it out
for 50 or 60 or 70 thousand dollars,

2162
01:49:38,412 --> 01:49:39,621
that's a huge profit,

2163
01:49:39,788 --> 01:49:41,999
and it's the American taxpayer
that's going to pay for that.

2164
01:49:42,165 --> 01:49:43,876
And it's going to get better!

2165
01:49:44,042 --> 01:49:47,546
Start building relationships
because it's going to get much better

2166
01:49:47,713 --> 01:49:49,631
as the oil flows
and their budget increase.

2167
01:49:49,798 --> 01:49:53,135
The good news is, whatever it costs,
the government will pay you.

2168
01:49:53,635 --> 01:49:56,138
War is always good for certain companies

2169
01:49:56,305 --> 01:49:58,515
that are in the war,
the business of war.

2170
01:49:58,682 --> 01:50:01,351
[chatter]

2171
01:50:01,518 --> 01:50:04,479
We're very proud of the work we're doing
in supporting the U.S. government

2172
01:50:04,646 --> 01:50:05,939
and the U.S. military,

2173
01:50:06,106 --> 01:50:08,609
and the real heroes of the campaign,
the real heroes of the reconstruction,

2174
01:50:08,775 --> 01:50:11,653
are the men and women
of the U.S. Armed Forces,

2175
01:50:11,820 --> 01:50:14,239
and we're proud of being any part of that
that we can in supporting them.

2176
01:50:14,740 --> 01:50:17,242
[voice over]
<i>Halliburton delivers hot meals, supplies,</i>

2177
01:50:17,784 --> 01:50:21,288
<i>clean clothing
<i>and communications to our soldiers.</i></i>

2178
01:50:21,455 --> 01:50:25,209
<i>So they can be a little closer to home.</i>

2179
01:50:25,375 --> 01:50:28,462
[emotional]
It's a girl? It's a girl!

2180
01:50:28,629 --> 01:50:29,838
[all cheer and laugh]

2181
01:50:30,005 --> 01:50:31,632
[voice over]
<i>Proud to serve our troops.</i>

2182
01:50:31,798 --> 01:50:35,385
I just read in the paper
how Halliburton got another contract.

2183
01:50:35,552 --> 01:50:38,472
-Halliburton got another contract!
-That's right!

2184
01:50:38,639 --> 01:50:41,308
Which is not being...

2185
01:50:42,476 --> 01:50:43,852
contested at all!

2186
01:50:44,019 --> 01:50:45,312
[Evelyn]
Because nobody knows!

2187
01:50:45,479 --> 01:50:47,814
Well, it's in the papers,
so somebody knows!

2188
01:50:48,148 --> 01:50:52,152
But that's after it happens,
it's after the fact, it's too late.

2189
01:50:52,319 --> 01:50:53,362
[throbbing of machinery]

2190
01:50:53,529 --> 01:50:57,324
[TV reporter]<i> The United States is now
<i>a major player in the Iraqi oil business.</i></i>

2191
01:50:57,491 --> 01:50:59,576
<i>American troops guard the oil fields</i>

2192
01:50:59,743 --> 01:51:02,788
<i>as Texas oil workers
<i>assess their potential.</i></i>

2193
01:51:02,955 --> 01:51:04,957
[worker]
<i>It's a safe environment to work in.</i>

2194
01:51:05,499 --> 01:51:08,460
We don't feel any risk,
we feel we're being well protected here,

2195
01:51:08,627 --> 01:51:09,628
or we wouldn't be here.

2196
01:51:09,795 --> 01:51:15,551
It's no secret, I mean, I make,
between 2,000 and 3,000 a month.

2197
01:51:15,717 --> 01:51:17,678
A Halliburton employee
out here driving a bus

2198
01:51:17,845 --> 01:51:20,347
can make all between
8,000 and 10,000 a month,

2199
01:51:20,514 --> 01:51:23,308
explain that one to me,
for 40 hours a week,

2200
01:51:23,475 --> 01:51:25,394
driving the same
two and a half mile route.

2201
01:51:25,561 --> 01:51:28,981
Go figure! Where do you...
Where's the justification in that?

2202
01:51:29,147 --> 01:51:32,484
There's no other single area
of the world today

2203
01:51:32,651 --> 01:51:36,238
with the opportunity for business,
new business,

2204
01:51:36,405 --> 01:51:39,324
similar to the opportunity
that's available today in Iraq.

2205
01:51:39,741 --> 01:51:42,077
The president went in and did what he did

2206
01:51:42,244 --> 01:51:44,371
and we're all supporting him
and our troops

2207
01:51:44,538 --> 01:51:49,418
and we wanna make sure
that the efforts and the lost lives and...

2208
01:51:49,585 --> 01:51:51,295
It wasn't for no reason.

2209
01:51:51,461 --> 01:51:53,714
If it wasn't for the oil,
no one would be there.

2210
01:51:53,881 --> 01:51:55,340
Nobody would worry about it.

2211
01:51:55,507 --> 01:51:57,176
Unfortunately,
at least for the near term,

2212
01:51:57,342 --> 01:52:02,639
we think it's going to be a good situation
and a dangerous situation.

2213
01:52:02,806 --> 01:52:05,267
Good for business, bad for the people.

2214
01:52:05,434 --> 01:52:08,937
[Bertha] Today, on the news,
Rumsfeld was saying...

2215
01:52:09,104 --> 01:52:11,773
And Wolf? Wolfowitz!

2216
01:52:11,940 --> 01:52:16,904
They were saying: "Oh, the Iraqi people
are much, much better off.

2217
01:52:17,070 --> 01:52:20,157
Isn't it better
that we got rid of Saddam

2218
01:52:20,324 --> 01:52:24,077
and now the Iraqi people can do
what they want to do

2219
01:52:24,244 --> 01:52:26,079
and really be free?"

2220
01:52:26,496 --> 01:52:29,208
Will they ever be free?
No, they'll not be free.

2221
01:52:29,374 --> 01:52:32,419
And where are the weapons
of mass destruction?

2222
01:52:32,586 --> 01:52:35,380
It was a... We were duped.
We were really duped.

2223
01:52:35,547 --> 01:52:40,511
And these poor people, the young men
and women who are being killed there,

2224
01:52:40,677 --> 01:52:43,096
it's unnecessary.
I... That's it!

2225
01:52:43,263 --> 01:52:44,806
-No more.
-[Evelyn] That's a disgrace.

2226
01:52:44,973 --> 01:52:48,769
They died in a just cause
for defending freedom

2227
01:52:48,936 --> 01:52:51,355
and they will not have died in vain.

2228
01:52:51,522 --> 01:52:57,110
